<HEAD>Car Salesman Says He Was Fired After Wearing Ugly Sport Coats</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT LEISNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Grant </PERSON>'s boss says the veteran salesman was fired because of his unseemly habit of wearing loud and ugly sport coats. <PERSON> Grant </PERSON>, 62, had filed a discrimination suit to prove he was forced out because of his age. <PERSON> Grant </PERSON> said before he lost his job at <LOCATION> Darby </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Buick </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Sarasota </LOCATION> in May 1985, the dealership was undergoing a `` new image'' campaign and he was told to start wearing sport coats on the used car lot for a more professional look. The 30-year sales veteran promptly went shopping for two jackets he describes as a pale pink and a rainbow plaid. He said the latter has every color in it and goes well with his gray slacks or green or red or blue. `` I saw nothing wrong with them,'' <PERSON> Grant </PERSON> said in a sworn statement in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Tampa </LOCATION>. At 6-foot-8, he said, he has to buy his clothes at specialty shops that fit tall men. And he wanted coats to go with his different trousers. `` So that's what I bought, you know, because I had gray pants, blue pants, green pants, every kind. So you had to have something to go with all of them.'' But his boss, <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Conrad </PERSON> <PERSON> Darby </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, said that neither jacket went well with the image he was trying to create for his dealership. `` Rather than promote an image of professionalism, <PERSON> Grant </PERSON>'s selections took the opposite direction,'' an attorney for <ORGANIZATION> Darby </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Buick </ORGANIZATION> said in court documents `` One jacket was multi-colored ... and the other was a loud fuchsia color.'' In the lawsuit, wryly dubbed `` the dress of a salesman'' in courthouse corridors, <PERSON> Grant </PERSON> claims the dress code and other charges against him, including catnapping and snacking in the office, are pretexts to hide the real problem _ age bias. <PERSON> Grant </PERSON>, the oldest salesman and the dealership's top in used car sales in 1984, was replaced by a less experienced person in his 20s, was never reprimanded and had an excellent job performance record, said <PERSON> Grant </PERSON>'s attorney, <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Donnellan </PERSON>. <PERSON> Darby </PERSON>'s attorney, <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sizemore </PERSON>, acknowledged that <PERSON> Grant </PERSON> was among the best in the sales force. As a result, <PERSON> Sizemore </PERSON> said, there was no motive to fire <PERSON> Grant </PERSON> for age discrimination, only for his poor behavior. The case is expected to go to trial this month.
