<HEAD>Doctors Treat Blinded Kangaroo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A wallaroo apparently blinded by the milk of human kindness underwent cataract surgery by two doctors who volunteered their services and usually treat people. In Saturday's three-hour operation, Dr. <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> Weinstein </PERSON>, a family practitioner, and Dr. <PERSON> Gene </PERSON> <PERSON> Zdenek </PERSON>, an ophthalmologist, removed a marble-sized cataract from the eye of the animal, a stocky kangaroo. The doctors tentatively declared the operation a success. <PERSON> Weinstein </PERSON> said an improper diet probably blinded the animal, named <PERSON> Menehuni </PERSON>, who apparently had been blind most of its seven to 11 years. Milk sugars collect in the eyes of wallaroos and cause cataracts because the animals can not break them down, <PERSON> Weinstein </PERSON> said. `` This poor guy's condition illustrates the reason why most people should n't have exotic animals,'' <PERSON> Zdenek </PERSON> said. `` The people probably had no idea they were blinding their pet.'' State authorities took <PERSON> Menehuni </PERSON> from its owners and gave him to the Wildlife Way Station in the <ORGANIZATION> Angeles </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION>, a nonprofit group that cares for exotic and wild animals that are sick or abandoned. The surgery was performed for free at the station with the help of resident veterinarian <PERSON> Silvio </PERSON> <PERSON> Santinelli </PERSON>. <PERSON> Weinstein </PERSON> said it was the first time he had to worry about `` moving a patient's tail out of the way.''
