<SECOND>PM-Queens Drugs,0822</SECOND>
<HEAD>Community Where Cop Died Being Taken Over By Dealers</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MITCHELL LANDSBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Dorothy </PERSON> was coming downstairs for some tea when she heard five shots in the middle of the night. Right away she thought of police Sgt. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Byrne </PERSON>, sitting alone in a patrol car a block away, guarding the home of a threatened witness. `` I said, ` Oh my God, he's in trouble,''' she recalled. Now, sitting in her tidy living room in the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jamaica </LOCATION> section of <LOCATION> Queens </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Dorothy </PERSON> _ a middle-age woman afraid to give her last name _ mourns <PERSON> Byrne </PERSON>, 22, a rookie who police believe was slain on the orders of a jailed drug kingpin. And she mourns for her neighborhood of small wood-frame houses that once must have seemed promising to working-class people looking for a slice of prosperity. It does n't anymore. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jamaica </LOCATION> has been overwhelmed by drugs, especially crack, in an epidemic that reached a peak of violence in the murder of <PERSON> Byrne </PERSON>, who was guarding the home of a man who had complained about drug dealers. Although police have taken the neighborhood by storm in efforts to ferret out <PERSON> Byrne </PERSON>'s killers and drive away the drug merchants, residents remain cynical and scared. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jamaica </LOCATION>, solidly black and poor, has been a troubled neighborhood for a long time. It shows in peeling paint, sagging porches, abandoned storefronts. But things have taken a turn for the worse in the past few years and police, clergy and residents blame crack and the people who sell it. `` They have taken over, completely taken over,'' said City Councilman <PERSON> Archie </PERSON> <PERSON> Spigner </PERSON>, who represents <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jamaica </LOCATION>. `` Everywhere I go, there are complaints. Every community meeting I attend, the inevitable complaint is narcotics.'' The users commit other crimes to support their habits. Children, seeing drug dealers in flashy clothes and fancy cars, are drawn to the drug life. Lawbreakers are drawn to the neighborhood. And dealers engage in turf wars that endanger all around them. `` You hear gunshots here and you hear gunshots there,'' said <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Barnes </PERSON>, who lost a new television set and a videocassette recorder in a burglary he blames on drug addicts. `` If I had the money, I'd move.'' When crack first spread through <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> several years ago, experts said it was sold by small-time entrepreneurs who would buy an ounce of cocaine and process it into a flaky, smokable drug. But now officials say a new hierarchy of violent, well-armed drug kingpins is taking over the crack trade in <LOCATION> Queens </LOCATION>. `` It starts in a very low-key way,'' said <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Hopkins </PERSON>, who supervises the Street Research Unit of the state Division of Substance Abuse Services. An entrepreneur begins selling drugs in a neighborhood and builds up a reputation. Buyers begin driving into the neighborhood. After a while, the dealer's success comes to the attention of a nearby drug gang. They make him an offer that he ca n't refuse, `` Work for us or get killed.'' `` Once that organized group comes in there, you're dealing with guns and it's not easy to get rid of,'' <PERSON> Hopkins </PERSON> said. What makes a neighborhood susceptible to drug infestation, beyond having at least some drug users? <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Beshers </PERSON>, a demographer at <ORGANIZATION> Queens </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION>, believes that an influx of different ethnic groups into a neighborhood can create a breakdown in the social structure that is conducive to illegal activity. `` You get a loss of communication,'' <PERSON> Beshers </PERSON> said. He noted that <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jamaica </LOCATION> has seen an influx of <LOCATION> Asian </LOCATION> and West Indian immigrants who ca n't necessarily communicate well with each other or with the established residents, mostly blacks who grew up in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> or in the South. For <PERSON> Archie </PERSON> <PERSON> Spigner </PERSON>, the reason for the infestation in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jamaica </LOCATION> is more prosaic: `` The police just allowed it to exist. They just accepted it, and it became entrenched, it became institutionalized.'' The Police Department, shocked by <PERSON> Byrne </PERSON>'s murder, has set out to end such criticism. Police Commissioner <PERSON> Benjamin </PERSON> <PERSON> Ward </PERSON> announced plans last week for a new, 118-member Tactical Narcotics Team whose mission is to stamp out drug dealing in southeast <LOCATION> Queens </LOCATION>. And an intense investigation has already led to the indictment of four men on charges of murdering the young cop. But skepticism runs high in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jamaica </LOCATION>, where some residents are bitter that it took the murder of a police officer to bring attention to their plight. `` What about the kids being killed in the drug wars?'' asked a man who walked down a street a block from the murder site and refused to give his name. `` That's what people ought to be crying about. I know about 10 cases of young kids getting killed in the neighborhood, and nobody ever did anything about that.''
