<BYLINE>Romare Bearden</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Romare </PERSON> <PERSON> Bearden </PERSON>, a leading American artist whose collages expressed the dignity of black people and Southern living, died Saturday. He was 75. <PERSON> Bearden </PERSON>'s work ranged from political cartoons to water colors, sets and costumes for the <PERSON> Alvin </PERSON> <PERSON> Ailey </PERSON> Dance Theater, public murals and eventually collages. He was awarded the National Medal of Arts by President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> in June. <PERSON> Lowery </PERSON> <PERSON> Sims </PERSON>, associate curator of 20th century art at the Metropolitan Museum of Art, said <PERSON> Bearden </PERSON>'s collages `` raised it to such a fine art it's hard to think of any other artist who is so closely associated with that medium.'' <PERSON> Bearden </PERSON> was born in <LOCATION> Charlotte </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, and grew up in <LOCATION> Harlem </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION>. He attended <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, majoring in mathematics and planning to become a doctor. He started drawing in college, and cartoons published in the Afro American, a weekly, led to a career in art.
