poll showing Simon with strong lead in Illinois; PICKS UP 8th graf
pvs bgng, `Simon and'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 With signs pointing to another <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> primary victory by <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, the vice president came under renewed criticism Sunday from GOP rival <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> and from Democrats <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> and <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> Jr.. Two polls published in Monday's editions of two newspapers gave contradictory indications of how the Democratic voters were expected to cast ballots in Tuesday's primary The poll in the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tribune </ORGANIZATION> showed <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> moving into the lead, favored by 32 percent of the Democrats, <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> Sen. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> by 29 percent and <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> by 20 percent. Five hundred likely Democratic primary voters were contacted Thursday and Friday and the survey had a margin of error of 5 percent, meaning the numbers could be off that much up or down. However, a poll for <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> showed <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> holding a strong lead with 42 percent, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> 33 percent, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> 14 percent, Sen. <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Tennessee </ORGANIZATION> 4 percent, Rep. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Missouri </ORGANIZATION> 3 percent and others and undecided, 4 percent. That poll was based on telephone interviews Friday night and Saturday with 287 Democratic voters who were likely to cast ballots. The margin of error was 6 percent. <PERSON> Simon </PERSON>, dependent on a home-state victory to remain in the race, said he had overcome poor showings in polls during other campaigns. `` If I get my message across to the people of <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, they're going to vote for me,'' he said The new <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tribune </ORGANIZATION> poll indicated slippage in <PERSON> Simon </PERSON>'s support A survey published in the <ORGANIZATION> Tribune </ORGANIZATION> on Sunday said the senator was leading with support from 35 percent of likely Democratic voters, while <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> had the backing of 30 percent and <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> that of 18 percent. <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> and <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> also traded barbs on the question of whether the Democratic nomination would be determined by a brokered convention next July in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Tribune </ORGANIZATION> poll on Sunday also showed <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> with a 34-point lead over <PERSON> Dole </PERSON>. The newspaper did not continue surveying Republicans. <PERSON> Dole </PERSON>, struggling to revive his presidential campaign, insisted he would fight on `` full bore'' after <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> though he said he had no obligation `` to look ridiculous.'' <PERSON> Gore </PERSON>, who hopes to demonstrate some Northern support in <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, said he would `` almost certainly'' turn down his party's vice presidential nomination <PERSON> Gore </PERSON>, at a campaign stop later, also blasted <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> over the Iran-Contra affair. `` The Reagan-Bush administration violated the law in a brazen way,'' he said, adding: `` We still do n't know what <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s role was. Interviewed on the CBS show, `` Face the Nation,'' <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> said he received telegram from former President <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> who urged him `` hang in there, do n't give up, make <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> your finest hour.'' `` I believe I have some obligation _ not to look ridiculous _ but some obligation to stay in this race,'' said the <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> senator. Asked if there was any chance he's drop out after <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> said, `` We're going full bore'' on the <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION>, which holds its primary on April 5. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> attended a Polish-language Mass at <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hyacinth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> on the city's northwest side and described his trip to <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> last year and his meeting with Solidarity leader <PERSON> Lech </PERSON> <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON>. `` It is the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> that must keep alive the hope of the Polish people,'' the vice president told a crowd that filled the church and spilled onto the sidewalk outside. After church, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> planned a day of appearances at shopping malls and restaurants, each event described by his staff as a `` photo opportunity only.'' On the possibility of a brokered convention, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said, `` I ca n't imagine anything worse _ the idea of taking the right of the people to elect their president with their votes and putting it in some backrooms in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Simon </PERSON>, predicting no Democrat would be able win the nomination on the first ballot at the convention, said <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' attitude demonstrated `` a touch of arrogance.'' He described the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> governor as saying, `` You either vote for me or you'll have a brokered convention.'' <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> also came to <PERSON> Simon </PERSON>'s defense and criticized <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, saying, `` Gov. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' commercial tries to lump him in with back-room politics of a kind <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> has not been associated with.'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, fresh from a victory in Democratic caucuses in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> on Saturday where he won 54 percent of the vote and picked up 23 delegates, said he hoped by the end of the primary and caucus season in June to have received `` a majority of the popular vote.'' Asked about the prospects of running against <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> in the general election, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said on the <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> show, `` Meet the Press,'' `` He certainly has a lot of baggage. `` <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was supposed to be over the commission on the drug situation, yet drugs are coming into this country at a rate that threatens our national security. ... To that continuous flow of drugs, Mrs. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> says no and <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> says nothing.'' The latest <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> delegate count showed <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> the Democratyic leader with 460 and <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> second with 423. <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> was third with 352. A total of 2,082 is needed for the nomination. On the Republican side, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> had 705 and <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> 165, with 1,139 need for the nomination. <PERSON> Gore </PERSON>, who received 18 percent of the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> vote and 6 delegates, said he consideed that `` a very good showing.'' `` I do n't know of anyone weho was surprised to see <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> win a big victory in his home state, his native state,'' the <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> senator said on `` Face the Nation.'' <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> denied he dislikes <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, but said, `` I do believe that he's sort of had a charmed life in politics, he's gotten quite a ways without doing very much Maybe that's a key to success I had n't thought of. The senator renewed his debate challenge to <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and raised again the question of a possible tie between the vice president and Panamanian strong man Gen. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> who has been accused of involvement in drug trafficking. `` I'd like <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to tell us whether <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> was on his payroll when he was <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> director,'' said <PERSON> Dole </PERSON>. As for his prospects for a comeback, <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> said, `` Sooner or later, the voters in one of these states are going to say, wait a minute, we're about to nominate someone who ca n't win in November.''
