` In <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> ... I want to win another gold medal,'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said, noting his strong showing in the Super Tuesday primaries. `` I hope to walk away with the majority,'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said. `` I should be the favorite son from <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON>, who was campaigning in <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>, congratulated <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> on his victory, saying `` I thought he would do very well there - it's his home state - and he did. <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> spokesman <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> called his candidate's performance `` a strong showing'' and added `` we expect to pick up a majority of the uncommitted.'' <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> officials expected as many as 20,000 voters would participate in the caucuses in which 44 convention delegates were at stake. During a campaign swing across the state Friday, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> predicted he would emerge as the leader in the muddled race for convention delegates once the votes are tallied in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, which holds a primary on Tuesday. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> trails <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> but leads <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> in the race for delegates to the Democratic National Convention. <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> has waged an active campaign in the state and a newspaper survey of <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> chairmen statewide found <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> expected to finish second to <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>. In the past, <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carolina </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democrats </ORGANIZATION> have had a penchant for going to the caucuses and voting for uncommitted delegates. <PERSON> Ja