<FIRST>r w AM-Budget Bjt   03-13 0676</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Budget, Bjt,680</SECOND>
<HEAD>Despite Summit Agreement, Requests Mounting for More 1988 Federal
Spending</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The highly touted budget summit agreement, long since enacted into law, definitively settled the question of how much money the federal government should spend this year. Right? Wrong. Congressional leaders are girding for a fight over whether spending in fiscal year 1988, which is nearly half over, needs to be increased. Whether lawmakers adhere to the summit pact and only provide extra money for what the agreement called `` dire emergencies'' rests on whether they succumb to the urge to spend more _ an urging fueled by the fact that this is an election year. In an era of $ 1 trillion federal budgets, requests for an additional several billion dollars for unforeseen needs are made by the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and approved by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> virtually every year. They are called supplemental spending bills. But the budget pact concluded by President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and congressional leaders forbade supplementals `` except in the case of dire emergency.'' The term was left undefined. Lawmakers are already beginning to submit new spending proposals said to be for dire emergencies. One, with 37 co-sponsors, would provide $ 105 million to the financially strapped <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION>. Another, with 20 co-sponsors, would add $ 263 million in spending for the homeless. `` My experience around here is it's sort of like a pent-up lake and the dam could break very easily,'' Sen. <PERSON> Pete </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Domenici </PERSON> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, senior Republican on the <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> and one of the negotiators at last fall's budget summit, says of the congressional proclivity for spending money. House Speaker <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, said last week that he interprets dire emergencies to include crises such as natural disasters or military operations. `` Aside from that kind of thing, it's not our expectation, nor our intention'' to approve other kinds of new spending, <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> said. Indeed, many lawmakers seem to believe that in this election year it could be bad politics to openly preach more spending because of the effect on the deficit. There is another reason for Democrats to be leery of a supplemental spending bill. Many of them believe it could become a way for aid to the Nicaraguan Contra rebels to be restored. `` The administration will ultimately use the supplemental for Contra aid,'' predicts Rep. <PERSON> Vic </PERSON> <PERSON> Fazio </PERSON>, D-Calif. Despite those incentives, some are pessimistic that lawmakers seeking new spending will be thwarted. `` They'll be caving, and it's unfortunate,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Delbert </PERSON> <PERSON> Latta </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, ranking Republican on the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> and another summit participant. `` It seems like per usual, everybody's got their program they're particularly interested in that's just not getting enough money. Lawmakers will be watching closely this week, when the administration says it will submit a supplemental spending bill of its own. The package is expected by congressional aides to be worth between $ 1 billion and $ 2 billion, but administration officials say it will produce no red ink. Instead, they say the spending for veterans, black lung benefits, the judicial branch, <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION>, prisons and other programs will be offset by cuts in other unspecified areas. If legislators believe that some of the spending in <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s request is not truly for emergencies, some lawmakers might be encouraged to press for money for programs they favor Under any circumstances, some members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> might try to attach their requests for new spending to the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> proposal. Such requests, once submitted, might be hard for other lawmakers to resist, especially with elections coming in a few months. For example, the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> guard </ORGANIZATION>, because it is low on money, has already announced plans to curtail more than half of its drug enforcement patrols and to close several facilities. Members could be hard-pressed to vote against restoring such cuts. Even if such efforts lose, lawmakers lose nothing by introducing them and showing their constituents that at least they tried. `` This is how they start brewing the stew,'' said one congressional aide, who asked not to be identified, about how extra spending gets generated.
</TEXT>
