<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 As many as 5,000 machines designed to monitor babies at risk of sudden infant death syndrome have faulty alarms that could leave infants vulnerable to death or injury, warns the company that makes them. The devices, manufactured by <ORGANIZATION> Aequitron </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, are designed to sound an alarm if an infant suddenly stops breathing or has an abnormal heart rate. But the machines have a `` higher than acceptable failure rate,'' the company's president, <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, said last week. The company issued a safety alert, warning dealers about the defect in its new model, No. 9200, which has been shipped to homes and hospitals nationwide since last July. The alert does not affect about 40,000 earlier models. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said that no injuries or deaths have been reported, but that the company learned within the last two or three weeks that the alarm had failed in some instances. The device primarily is used in homes to monitor children believed to be at high risk for SIDS. The mysterious malady is the seventh leading killer of younger Americans, according to the national <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION>. In some cases, the infants suffer from apnea, a tendency to stop breathing while asleep, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said. If the alarm sounds in time, an adult often can awaken the child and restart his or her breathing. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said the company is notifying its dealers about the problem by registered letter. The dealers will alert individual customers, who lease the machines for home use.
