<HEAD>Ershad Tally Rises to 249 in Parliamentary Vote</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Hussain </PERSON> <PERSON> Muhammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Ershad </PERSON>'s party increased its already wide margin in <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> by picking up two more seats in weekend repolling, the <ORGANIZATION> Election </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> announced Sunday Voting was held Saturday in nine districts where violence during the main election March 3 had forced it to be called off. At least 13 people were killed and 300 others injured in clashes March 3, and two more people died in bomb blasts in <LOCATION> Dhaka </LOCATION> during repolling Saturday, police said. The country's major opposition parties, which have been waging a campaign since November to oust <PERSON> Ershad </PERSON>, boycotted the Parliament balloting. They contend that fair elections can not be held until <PERSON> Ershad </PERSON> resigns and have denounced the latest vote as fraudulent. <PERSON> Ershad </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Jatiya </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> had 249 seats in the 330-member house, according to the latest results. The <ORGANIZATION> Election </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> said the <ORGANIZATION> Combined </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Opposition </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, a coalition of scores of small groups, won 18 seats. Two minor parties won two seats each, and independents won 25 seats. The results in three districts have not yet been announced. In one district, where a candidate was killed, voting has been scheduled for April 7. Another 30 seats in <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> are reserved for women, who are chosen later. The major opposition parties contend that less than 1 percent of the nation's 48 million registered voters cast ballots in the Parliament elections. But government officials say the turnout appeared to be more than 50 percent. <PERSON> Ershad </PERSON> scheduled the elections after dissolving