<FIRST>r a AM-LouisianaGovernor Bjt   03-13 0695</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Louisiana Governor, Bjt,0713</SECOND>
<HEAD>Roemer Says He Will Mix Dreams With Reality</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN SAYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> `` Buddy'' <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, a brash self-styled reformer who unseated a political legend to take office Monday as governor, says he faces `` a difficult and interesting job'' in trying to solve <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>'s problems. `` I think I'm just a representative of the people in this. I think it's a make-or-break situation for the kinds of things we want,'' <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON>, 44, said in a recent interview. As Gov. <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON> leaves office, the state faces the immediate problems of a four-year, $ 1.2 billion budget deficit and a cash shortage that threatens to shut down state government. Fiscal analysts have warned that the state faces as much as a $ 1 billion shortfall for the 1988-89 fiscal year. The state's unemployment rate hit 12 percent in January, one of the highest in the nation, due primarily to the long-running downturn in the oil and gas industry. At the same time, <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>'s education systems are under challenge as second-rate, business interests are demanding a major overhaul of the state's tax system in order to attract new industry, and environmental groups are calling for tougher regulations to protect the air and water. <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON>, who plans major reforms in those areas and others such as in campaign finance practices, said the challenge is unlike that facing any other <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> governor. `` We need a combination in the next four years of a crisis manager and a long-term planner,'' he said. `` It's rare that you combine the two. That's what I'm going to have to do as governor. `` But I've got to do both to get us out of debt and build _ education development, economic development, better environment. It's going to be a difficult and interesting job.'' To get started, the Democratic former congressman is planning a low-budget inauguration minus the traditional parade and inaugural night ball. According to his transition office, only $ 48,000 will be spent on the entire event, less than the $ 60,000 Gov. <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> <PERSON> Treen </PERSON> spent on the stage used for his swearing-in ceremony in 1980. <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON>, who campaigned on the need for a `` revolution'' to turn around the state's declining fortunes, said the first year of his administration will be dedicated to reversing the financial problems and creating a new image for <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>, often associated with scandal. `` Confidence, attitude and legislative programs _ and then we will slowly fund them over the next four years,'' he said. `` This plan wo n't be magic, it wo n't be instant. We've had to build from the ground up. But I'm very pleased with the progress we've made.'' <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON>, who served as governor from 1972 to 1980 and returned for a third term in 1984, was occupied for much of his last administration defending himself successfully against federal racketeering charges. As solutions for the state's budget problems, he proposed a statewide lottery and casino gambling in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON> is opposed to both. <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON> said he was happy that <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON> was willing to help during the transition between the Oct. 24 election and Monday's inauguration At <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON>'s request <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON> appointed <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Kendrick </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Baton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> department store executive, as commissioner of administration. <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON> also approved about $ 36 million in budget cuts requested by <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON>, but shielded the giant <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> from the fiscal ax. <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON> is considering splitting the agency into two departments as part of a reorganization program to be studied by a special legislative session later this month. Short-term budget reductions also will be on the agenda. <PERSON> Kendrick </PERSON> has spearheaded efforts to minimize the cash-flow problem by pushing back more than $ 480 million in expenditures until the new fiscal year begins July 1. The cash-saving measures include delaying payments to government retirement systems, holding state income tax refund checks for 90 days and pushing one state payday back. In the meantime, <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON> said he will cut the budget back as far as he can before the subject of taxes is broached. `` We are not going to raise taxes or change taxes until we cut this budget,'' <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON> said. `` It is out of control.''
