<FIRST>r i AM-Gorbachev-Yugoslavia     03-13 0683</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gorbachev-Yugoslavia,0707</SECOND>
<HEAD>Visit May Offer Soviet Leader Comparisons To Soviet Reform</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL PUTZEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> will spend five days in this communist country studying economic and social problems that he hopes the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> can avoid as it embraces reform. <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>, which has jealously guarded its independence from <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> power for 40 years, presents a picture of prosperity to a visitor from <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. A crush of private automobiles in the capital and store windows displaying local and Western-made consumer goods of every description make <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s truck-cluttered streets and drab facades seem all the more barren. But the country's system of `` self-managed, market socialism'' is struggling with high inflation, high unemployment, widespread labor unrest and a paralyzing $ 20 billion debt to Western creditors. And <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s leadership must constantly perform a delicate balancing act to prevent the country from being torn apart by nationalistic rivalries within its borders. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> arrives here Monday for a five-day visit that includes <LOCATION> Belgrade </LOCATION>, the northern industrial city of <LOCATION> Ljubljana </LOCATION> and the southern resort city of <LOCATION> Dubrovnik </LOCATION> on the <LOCATION> Adriatic </LOCATION>. The Soviet leader, who has just marked the end of his third year in power, is trying to boost the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> out of economic stagnation. He has decentralized control over production and introduced market forces to shake workers and managers out of their notorious complacency. During his tour <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> may gain some pointers on his programs of `` perestroika,'' or restructuring of the Soviet economy, and `` glasnost,'' which encourages more open expression of ideas for solving the nation's problems. With the development in recent years of a free-wheeling press and a mixed economy that encourages both private enterprise and central planning, <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION> offers something of a window on the future for the reform-minded Soviet leader. Runaway inflation and the government's powerless decrees aimed at curing the country's economic ills serve notice that the path may not be an easy one. In recent months, as ethnic minorities have attempted to take advantage of the Soviet government's new tolerance to express their long-held grievances, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> has faced challenges from nationalists of several stripes. Despite some rioting and huge mass demonstrations in the southern republics of <LOCATION> Azerbaidjian </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>, no Soviet ethnic group has the strength that <LOCATION> Yugoslavian </LOCATION> nationalities have used to guarantee each a share of governing power at the expense of the central authorities. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> is the first Soviet leader to visit <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION> since the death of <PERSON> Josip </PERSON> <PERSON> Broz </PERSON> <PERSON> Tito </PERSON> in May 1980. <PERSON> Tito </PERSON> broke with <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> in 1948 and steered a stubbornly independent course outside the Soviet bloc. After being forced by a Soviet-led blockade to open trade with the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION> has since re-established economic ties with <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> today is <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s largest trading partner, with the Yugoslavs importing primarily crude oil and other raw materials and exporting manufactured goods, including much-prized shoes, clothing and technology to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. A $ 1.4 billion trade surplus is a subject of concern in <LOCATION> Belgrade </LOCATION>, but there has been speculation the Soviets may agree to pay off their paper debt by building a subway system for the traffic-clogged Yugoslav capital. The present <LOCATION> Yugoslav </LOCATION> leadership, headed by an eight-member state presidency, has continued <PERSON> Tito </PERSON>'s independent political course, and <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION> remains an important nation in the non-aligned movement. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> is expected to formally acknowledge that special status with the issuance during his visit of a joint declaration guaranteeing full Yugoslavian independence. But in the context of his public statements in <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION> and to fellow <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> leaders in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> last year, the <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> declaration may signal more independence for other East European nations as well. The Soviet leader has said his nation has no monopoly on the proper path to socialism, and reform-minded leaders elsewhere in <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> are expected to test his words with experiments aimed at reinvigorating their own economies. Yugoslav deputy foreign minister, <PERSON> Ilija </PERSON> <PERSON> Djukic </PERSON>, has said the new Soviet-Yugoslav document would update previous declarations signed by the two countries in 1955 and 1956 and will `` further confirm principles of non-interference on the basis of equality and soveregnty.''
