<HEAD>Infighting Plagues Afghan Guerrilla Factions</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Afghanistan, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN WILDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> ISLAMABAD </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> -LRB- ap -RRB- _ <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>'s tough stand at the slow-moving Afghan peace talks has touched off a power struggle among guerrilla leaders fighting the Soviet-backed Afghan government. <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> Prime Minister <PERSON> Mohammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Khan </PERSON> <PERSON> Junejo </PERSON> has been barnstorming the country to drum up support for his demand that an accord on a Soviet troop withdrawal be coupled with a plan for a future <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> government. In the meantime, the fractious guerrilla alliance, whose factions all want a voice in that new government, has been plagued by upheaval. During the weekend, <PERSON> Yunis </PERSON> <PERSON> Khalis </PERSON> resigned as chairman of the seven-party alliance, ostensibly for health reasons. But there were numerous reports, unconfirmed by guerrilla spokesmen, that the 69-year-old <LOCATION> Khalis </LOCATION> quit to protest plans to send a resistance delegation to the U.N.-sponsored peace talks at <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>, which resume Monday. Another insurgent leader, <PERSON> Sibghatullah </PERSON> <PERSON> Mojaddedi </PERSON>, pulled his moderate <ORGANIZATION> Afghan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> out of the alliance complaining of undue pressure from the body's four-party majority of Moslem extremists. Two days later, <PERSON> Mojaddedi </PERSON> returned to the fold, saying he had received `` certain assurances'' from the fundamentalists and from Pakistani officials. He did not elaborate. There has been intense Pakistani pressure on the guerrillas to come up with an acceptable plan for forming a transitional government that would preside over the withdrawal of the estimated 115,000 Soviet troops who back <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>'s communist rulers. <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION