acceptable to a majority of Afghans. <LOCATION> Khalis </LOCATION>'s resignation, meanwhile, threatened to widen the split because the next leader in line for the rotating chairmanship is <PERSON> Gulbaddin </PERSON> <PERSON> Hekmatyar </PERSON>, head of the Hezb-i-Islami and the most extremist Moslem guerrilla of all. While fending off acusations that his fighters have attacked rival groups inside <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Hekmatyar </PERSON> recently had taken to upstaging <LOCATION> Khalis </LOCATION> by calling press conferences of his own to promote <ORGANIZATION> Hezb-i-Islami </ORGANIZATION>'s hardline vision of a fundamentalist Islamic regime. <PERSON> Mohammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Uaqub </PERSON> <PERSON> Sharafat </PERSON>, press spokesman for the alliance, said there were plans to send a guerrilla delegation to the <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> talks to help clear up the confusion over the insurgents' stand. Even that move threatened to cause a rift. <PERSON> Rasul </PERSON> <PERSON> Sayyaf </PERSON>, leader of the Ittehad party, issued a statement Sunday declaring his opposition to sending a delegation. `` And under no circumstances shall we agree to any kind of direct or indirect talks with the <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> regime or the -LRB- ruling <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Afghanistan </ORGANIZATION> -RRB-,'' he said. Pakistani officials publicly have urged the guerrillas to soften their stand in the interest of peace. But so far, the extremists among the insurgents have equated compromise with capitulation.
