<HEAD>Where the Boys Were: The Demise of Spring Break</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD W. SWINTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The floods of vacationing students that once deluged this seaside community each spring have gone, leaving some hoteliers broken and the city rethinking its economy. Only 100,000 college students are expected to bask this year on the subtropical sands, made famous in the 1960 movie `` Where the Boys Are.'' There were 350,000 in 1985. The loss of business has prompted 12 smaller hotels that depended on the student crush to auction off their properties together April 7, said <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> DeMastry </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Fisher </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Auction </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Company </ORGANIZATION>. Having paid top dollar for hotels in the early 1980 boom years, many of them now can not meet their mortgage payments. By selling en masse, they hope to gain high prices by offering developers the opportunity to assemble large tracts. The unmanageable hordes of sunworshipping students, who packed hotel rooms by night and patronized businesses on the beach strip by day, divided this resort town. Beach-front nightspots, vendors and student-dependent hotels clamored for continued promotion of spring break. But their cries were overcome by the din of residents and year-round businesses, snarled in springtime traffic and furious about paying for police and cleaning up mountains of trash. Since 1986, when city leaders used strict law enforcement to quell the riotous partying, the city and <LOCATION> Broward </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> have been trying to diversify their tourist clientele. Last year, word of strict police enforcement of parking, drinking, and code regulations discouraged student visitors, costing merchants $ 40 million and 100,000 student customers. The <ORGANIZATION> Broward </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tourist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> said the 200,000 student visitors spent about $ 80 million, one-third less than the $ 120 million tally from 1986, in the <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lauderdale </LOCATION> area. Police made about 1,300 arrests during last year's spring break, with college students comprising about one-third of them. There were 2,506 arrests in 1986. <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lauderdale </LOCATION> is experiencing a `` shaking out,'' said <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Handevidt </PERSON>, who plans to sell his <ORGANIZATION> Orton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Terrace </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Apartment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hotel </ORGANIZATION> at the auction. `` What's happened is the city has said, ` Whoa! We ca n't deal with this,''' <PERSON> Handevidt </PERSON> said of spring break. `` It was bad in 1985. I do n't know anyone who would say differently.'' The atmosphere of drunkenness, littered streets and the stench from people urinating in the streets drove people away, he said. `` The money's just not coming in, so people are selling out,'' said the manager of a small hotel, who spoke on condition of anonymity. `` We're losing money every week.'' <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lauderdale </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Broward </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> can not depend on a seasonal tourism, officials said. The beach businesses are beginning to understand that, said <PERSON> Nickie </PERSON> <PERSON> Grossman </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Broward </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> commissioner and chairwoman of the <ORGANIZATION> Tourism </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>. `` We want every tourist'' _ from <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Yankees </ORGANIZATION> fans during baseball's spring training to <ORGANIZATION> Miami </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dolphins </ORGANIZATION> fans and the teams the <ORGANIZATION> Dolph