<SECOND>AM-Waldheim Show,870</SECOND>
<HEAD>British Producer Lines Up Witnesses Against Waldheim For TV Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HENRY GOTTLIEB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A British producer says he has lined up 70 witnesses, including some who served with <PERSON> Kurt </PERSON> <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON> in World War II, to give evidence at a televised `` trial'' of allegations the Austrian president was involved in Nazi atrocities. The list includes some of <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON>'s subordinates and superiors when he was an officer in the <ORGANIZATION> German </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> from 1939 to 1945, says <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Saltman </PERSON>, who is producing the show for broadcast on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and overseas television in June. `` It took a lot of persuasion to get some of them to do it,'' <PERSON> Saltman </PERSON> said in a recent interview. With cameras rolling, lawyers will spend nine days beginning April 13 examining witnesses as if they were in a court of law, before a panel of retired jurists, including <PERSON> Shirley </PERSON> <PERSON> Hufstedler </PERSON>, a former <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> education secretary and federal <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> judge. The program then will be edited down to four hours, ending with the judges' decision on whether there is probable cause that <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON> acted contrary to the international laws of war. `` Nobody has any idea how it will come out,'' <PERSON> Saltman </PERSON> says. `` There's astonishingly little control over it. That's the beauty of it.'' The show is the latest entrant in what <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON> himself has called a new `` cottage industry'' _ investigating whether the Austrian president knew about, supported or took part in atrocities when he served the Germans in <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION> during the war. Since the investigations began with a probe by the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jewish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in 1986, <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON> has been denounced around the world, been placed on a list of undesirables banned from entry to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and has become the focus of a bitter debate in his homeland. <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON> has denied taking part in atrocities. Indeed, <PERSON> Saltman </PERSON> says that in preparing for the show, he talked to the Austrian leader for nearly an hour to get <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON>'s side of the story. What did <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON> think of being `` tried'' on television? `` He was not overjoyed,'' <PERSON> Saltman </PERSON> said. `` I do n't think I'll be getting a Christmas card this year from <PERSON> Kurt </PERSON> <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON>.'' Nor will <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON> appear on the program. Work for the show began in May 1987, when producers at <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Thames </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> decided to do to <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON> what was done several years ago on a program called `` The Trial of <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON> <PERSON> Oswald </PERSON>'' That was a mock courtroom proceeding, using real attorneys, judges and witnesses to the shooting of President <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> in 1963 to determine if <PERSON> Oswald </PERSON> was guilty of the crime For aesthetic and legal reasons and because the participating witnesses and lawyers would have objected, <PERSON> Saltman </PERSON> and his colleagues at <ORGANIZATION> Thames </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> and co-producing Home Box Office cringe when anyone uses the word `` trial'' when describing what they are doing to <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON>. They want to avoid comparisons with the daily syndicated <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> show, `` People's Court,'' where a real judge settles such issues as `` The Case of the Busted Headlight.'' The show will be a `` commission of inquiry,'' with retired jurists from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION> hearing testimony elicited by a `` presenting counselor,'' <PERSON> Allan </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON>, former director of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Special </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investigation </ORGANIZATION> _ the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s Nazi-hunting wing. Lord <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Rawlinson </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s attorney general from 1970 to 1974, will be the `` challenging counsel,'' trying to rebut the evidence against <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON>. The proceedings will be filmed in a courtroom built for the program. Then the judges will deliberate privately for as long as they think necessary and then deliver their opinions to the cameras a few days before the show goes on the air. Like the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, they may not agree. And like the high court, no one _ not even the producers _ will be allowed to hear the deliberations. The rules of evidence will be similar to those used in grand jury proceedings and the judgment will not be whether <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON> is guilty, but whether there is enough evidence to bring an indictment. `` This is about as close as anyone is going to get to bringing the <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON> case into a court of law,'' <PERSON> Saltman </PERSON> said. `` No matter what we call it, the audience is going to say ` this is the trial of <PERSON> Kurt </PERSON> <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON>' and they're going to sit at home, and decide if he's a fascist,'' the producer said. According to evidence already made public, <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON> was a German intelligence officer familiar with reprisals against civilians to stop guerrilla activities in <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>. Questions have also been raised about whether he was involved in deportation of Greek Jews to death camps and mistreatment of Allied prisoners of war. The controversy has been heightened by the fact that for many years, notably during his years of service as <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> Secretary General, <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON> omitted all mention of his service in <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION> in his official biography. <PERSON> Saltman </PERSON> said a team of investigators hired by the producers scoured archives and searched for witnesses in <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Bulgaria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Albania </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. So far, stations in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Scandinavia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> and Australian have said they will show the program. Negotiations with a West German station are underway. Austrian television has also been offered a chance to buy the program, but there's no sign it will do so, <PERSON> Saltman </PERSON> said.
