We've answered many of the charges in his statement. There is nothing new there.'' The MX is the centerpiece of President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s nuclear build-up. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> originally wanted to build 100 of the missiles and put them in silos in <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION>, but <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> limited the total deployment to 50 because of fears about the weapon's vulnerability to a Soviet strike The <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> now wants to build 50 more and put them aboard trains. <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> has said he would like to put all 100 of the weapons aboard trains. The MX weapons tested thus far have shown better-than-expected accuracy, and the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> has consistently defended the ability of the weapons deployed to hit their targets. Thus far, 34 MX weapons have been deployed, but only 22 have the proper IMUs. The other dozen still lack guidance systems, <PERSON> Defrank </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> Northrop </ORGANIZATION> has promised to accelerate production of the guidance systems, and all 50 of the MX weapons are scheduled to be deployed by the end of 1988. One of the IMUs cited by <PERSON> Aspin </PERSON> failed after only 200 hours on alert atop an MX missile, according to his speech. That would mean that it fell far short of the service standard of 3,000 hours allowed between failures, he said. But <PERSON> Defrank </PERSON> said the 3,000 hours is a standard mean time, meaning it is an average. `` To criticize the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> for one <ORGANIZATION> IMU </ORGANIZATION> failing is meaningless because it's the mean time between failures that is important, and we're meeting that,'' he said.
