<HEAD>Women Head 300 Colleges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Women now head nearly 300 of the accredited colleges and universities in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> said Sunday. The number of women college presidents doubled from 148 in 1975 to 296 in 1987, with the most rapid growth at public institutions, said the council's Office of Women in Higher Education. But the fastest spurt was in the late 1970s and early 1980s, it said. There was a net increase of only 10 women presidents between 1984 and 1987. There are more than 3,400 two - and four-year colleges in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>; 2,880 are accredited Eighty-six of the women presidents, or 29 percent, are nuns heading religious institutions. Forty, or 14 percent, are minorities, including 22 black, 13 Hispanic, four American Indian and one <LOCATION> Asian-American </LOCATION> women. Since 1984, the office said, the number of women heading four-year public institutions has increased 22 percent, from 32 to 39. The number heading four-year private colleges and universities grew by 16 percent, from 134 to 156. Women also held the presidencies at 73 two-year public colleges -LRB- up from 72 in 1984 -RRB- and 28 two-year private institutions -LRB- down from 48 -RRB-. <PERSON> Donna </PERSON> <PERSON> Shavlik </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Women </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> in </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Higher </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION>, said colleges need to search harder and address inequities in hiring and promoting women. `` What's needed is personal and institutional commitment and determination to achieve the goal,'' she said.
