<HEAD>Coping With Power Failures, Competing With Vanna White: Dole
Fights On</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When a campaign starts to slide, as <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON>'s surely has, everything goes wrong, even the little things The candidate finds himself struggling to overcome power failures and competing for attention against <PERSON> Vanna </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON>. The signs are everywhere that <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has all but clinched the Republican presidential nomination. He won a smashing victory on Super Tuesday and appeared poised to keep rolling on Tuesday when <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> holds its primary. Yet, despite the battering he has taken from <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> in recent contests, <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> clearly sees a loser when he looks at the vice president. `` Sooner or later,'' he said Sunday on the <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> show `` Face the Nation,'' `` the voters in one of these states are going to say, wait a minute, we're about to nominate a loser.'' But <PERSON> Dole </PERSON>'s view was n't shared by many Republican voters in the South and does n't appear likely to find much support in <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>. In fact, if anyone looked like a loser, it was the senator from <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION>. After Super Tuesday, <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> needed a way to turn the race around. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> came out of the South with a big lead in delegates _ 705 to 165 _ but the next battleground was the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> had trounced <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> had his hands full as he started his <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> campaign, still stunned by the magnitude of his loss on Super Tuesday when <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> took all 16 primaries. Suddenly word got out that the campaign was laying off most of its paid staff and was pulling all its commercials off the air in <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>. Rumors spread swiftly that <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> was going to throw in the towel and concede the nomination to <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. That possibility clearly had been discussed and rejected. <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> said people were laid off because `` a campaign is not a jobs program'' and after Super Tuesday, paid staff was not needed in a large number of states. While that argument made some sense, the timing of the layoffs, right after a big loss, left the unmistakable impression the campaign was folding. The announcement on the television commercials was a case of different people in the same campaign giving out conflicting versions of what was happening. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Brock </PERSON>, the campaign manager, finally said on Friday that all the commercials had not been pulled. He said many had been dropped in favor of a decision to buy 30 minutes of time for a major <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> effort to win voter support. <PERSON> Brock </PERSON>'s version, as it turned out, was correct. Some 30-second <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> commercials are running in <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>. But the former secretary of labor was not around to provide an authoritative version when the word first got out. He was attending ceremonies marking the anniversary of the founding of the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> department </ORGANIZATION>. The 30-minute <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> program, originating from <ORGANIZATION> Knox </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Galesburg </LOCATION>, site of one of the Lincoln-Douglas debates, turned out to be a showcase of campaign disarray. Eight hours before the program was to air, <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> advisers were unable to say exactly what it would contain. Aides were scrambling to fill the 30 minutes. Nearly half of it was filled by a <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> biography filmed months ago for showing at campaign events. The message the candidate delivered was a restatement of campaign rhetoric, his contention that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was not discussing the issues. `` The issues are more important than the odds,'' he said, portraying himself as the one who was responsible for getting President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s program through <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. It was a $ 100,000 gamble _ and was all the riskier due to the decision to go live instead of taping the program in advance. In the middle of the program, there was an unexplained power failure that resulted in loss of the picture for several minutes. The sound was not interrupted. How many voters saw the program was questionable. It was competing against `` Wheel of Fortune,'' the popular game show in which Vanna White has become a celebrity for her role of turning around the letters on word puzzles. While <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> was fighting for attention in one campus building, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was addressing a cheering crowd of more than 1,000 Republicans in the college gymnasium about 200 yards away. Tied as tightly as ever to <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> condiently predicted, `` We are going to win on Tuesday because we have the people with us.'' In the battle for Republican primary votes, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is looking and sounding very much like a winner.
</TEXT>
