<HEAD>Restaurant To Give Homeless Alternative To Soup Line</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Inside an old brick building that once was a drive-in liquor store, a minister and a group of volunteers are putting the finishing touches on a cafe for people who rarely get to enjoy restaurant treatment. The cafe will be for the homeless, who have some of their basic needs met by the city's shelters and soup kitchens but are unable to enjoy the more relaxed and personal atmosphere of a restaurant, said the Rev. A.B. Short. `` I'm thankful for the feeding programs; they -LRB- the homeless -RRB- could n't survive without them,'' said <PERSON> Short </PERSON>, who has been involved in homeless aid programs since moving to <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> in 1980. `` But if you feed 500 people in two hours, you ca n't give much personal attention,'' he said. <PERSON> Short </PERSON> said the restaurant will be relatively small, serving about 30 at a time, and will emphasize a friendly atmosphere over merely providing food to the homeless. `` People have a need for food, but we hope the interaction and relationships will be our primary product,'' he said. The restaurant will feature counter service as well as tables. The kitchen will be entirely visible from the dining area so patrons can talk to the cooks, dishwashers and other volunteer staffers, <PERSON> Short </PERSON> said. One of the main differences from the standard shelter kitchen will be that the homeless will be able to choose items from a menu, instead of just having plates of food handed to them. There will be no charge for the food, but a voucher system of tickets distributed by area shelters may be used, <PERSON> Short </PERSON> said. A legal aid service as well as alcohol and drug abuse counseling also will be available on the premises, <PERSON> Short </PERSON> added. There are an estimated 7,000-10 ,000 homeless in the <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> area Renovation work began in November with the help of $ 30,000 in federal and state grants. Several individuals and businesses have contributed materials or funds, and some of the work has been done by volunteers, including members of the homeless community. `` The idea seems so unique it has sparked a lot of people's interest,'' <PERSON> Short </PERSON> said, adding that he hopes the restaurant will be ready to open by the end of the month Once it is open, much of the food will be provided by agencies that already help the homeless. <PERSON> Short </PERSON> said he also will rely on donations to keep the restaurant going. At first, the restaurant will serve for two hours beginning at noon. <PERSON> Short </PERSON> said he hopes he can add a breakfast or dinner period later. Short, 43, a native of <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>, said the idea for the restaurant grew from his involvement with the homeless, which started when he organized a shelter at <ORGANIZATION> Oakhurst </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Baptist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> in suburban <LOCATION> Decatur </LOCATION>, where he is a member. He said his church, which includes many social activists, responded enthusiastically to the shelter project. But he and his wife, who is on the faculty of <ORGANIZATION> Emory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, wanted to go a step further. `` We decided that if we were really serious about the homeless issues, what we might ought to be doing is having homeless people live with us,'' he said. They have had homeless people living with them since 1982, and some of them now are working on the restaurant, located near the Martin Luther King Jr.. Center for Nonviolent Social Change <PERSON> Short </PERSON> said he does not envision facilities such as the restaurant replacing traditional shelters or kitchens, but he would like to see it become an established part of the homeless aid network. `` It's just another piece of the very important work people are already involved in,'' he said.
