<HEAD>Austrian Jews Remember Nazi Terror</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 20th graf, `On Friday...' to CORRECT English translation
of title of play. Pick up 21st pvs, `The only...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Some of the few <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> Jews who survived <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON>'s death grip on <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION> gathered Sunday at a synagogue and at a former Gestapo headquarters, remembering the pain of the past and the shadow it has cast on the present. Prayers and tears mingled inside the city's oldest synagogue, where more than a thousand Jews marked the 50th anniversary of the Anschluss, <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>'s annexation by <ORGANIZATION> Nazi </ORGANIZATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. `` No one can feel our pain, no one can feel our suffering,'' Rabbi <PERSON> Chaim </PERSON> <PERSON> Eisenberg </PERSON> told the congregation. The meeting was the emotional climax of four days of solemn remembrances of the annexation. Political and cultural leaders engaged in an unprecedented public probing of their nation's role as victim and perpetrator of Nazi terror and continued to discuss the problem of President <PERSON> Kurt </PERSON> <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON>. For many <PERSON> Vienna </PERSON> <PERSON> Jews </PERSON>, <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON>'s concealment of his German army service in the <LOCATION> Balkans </LOCATION> symbolizes the suppression of the <ORGANIZATION> Nazi </ORGANIZATION> past in <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Grosz </PERSON>, leader of the Jewish community, drew loud applause at another meeting at the former <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> headquarters of the Nazi police when he expressed hope that Jewish suffering under the Nazis would be remembered. `` We can only hope that the high degree of consciousness for these events in recent days will not end next week,'' said <PERSON> Grosz </PERSON>. There were 200,000 Jews in <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> on March 1938, when <PERSON> Adolf </PERSON> <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON>'s troops swept into his native <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>. Today, just 6,000 Jews remain, a mix of Holocaust survivors and younger Jews from the Soviet bloc and <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. They have been exposed to a new wave of anti-Semitism in the past two years that has surfaced with the controversy over the <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON>'s World War II record. <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON> concealed his role as a German army lieutenant in the <LOCATION> Balkans </LOCATION> until it was disclosed in the media in March 1986. He has rejected calls for his resignation, saying he will stay in office until his term expires in 1992. A commission of historians appointed by the Austrian government to investigate <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON> said he was in a position to know about <ORGANIZATION> Nazi </ORGANIZATION> atrocities and did nothing to stop them. <PERSON> Grosz </PERSON> attacked <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON> backers who argue the president must stay in office to prevent a backlash against Jews if he is forced to resign. He said the Jews could defend themselves. By contrast, <PERSON> Grosz </PERSON> welcomed Socialist Chancellor <PERSON> Franz </PERSON> <PERSON> Vranitzky </PERSON> to the meeting as `` our good friend.'' <PERSON> Vranitzky </PERSON>, who is popular with <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION>'s Jews, also warned against losing sight of the <ORGANIZATION> Nazi </ORGANIZATION> past. `` In the last few days ... we all tried to make the things that happened seem anonymous in some way, as if we were afraid to make it too personal, too direct,'' <PERSON> Vranitzky </PERSON> said. `` You have to call things by their name,'' he said. `` It was not an anonymous horror that descended on a people ... and then disappeared.'' Referring to the former Gestapo headquarters, he noted, `` Let the desperate screams that sounded from the cellars of this site, which we can no longer hear, be a reminder.'' Half a mile away, at <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Opera </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, former Socialist Chancellor <PERSON> Bruno </PERSON> <PERSON> Kreisky </PERSON> reiterated his call for <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON> to resign, while Roman Catholic Cardinal <PERSON> Franz </PERSON> <PERSON> Koenig </PERSON> looked at the controversial role of the church in the Nazi era. `` The church did not do enough to protect -LRB- believers -RRB- against the temptations of the <ORGANIZATION> Nazi </ORGANIZATION> regime,'' <PERSON> Koenig </PERSON> said. On Friday night, neo-Nazis booed a <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> premiere of `` The Deputy,'' West German <PERSON> Rolf </PERSON> <PERSON> Hochhuth </PERSON>'s 1960s play on the church's World War II role The only other overt neo-Nazi action came in <LOCATION> Linz </LOCATION>, the city of <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON>'s youth, where a recording of <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON>'s 1938 speech in the town blared from a hotel just after a monument to <ORGANIZATION> Nazi </ORGANIZATION> victims was unveiled Saturday. Police found no trace of the perpetrators.
