<HEAD>Wildcat Strike At Rome Airport Cancels And Delays Flights</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Scores of flights were canceled or delayed at <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION>'s main airport Sunday after ground workers staged a wildcat strike because they were unhappy with a tentative accord reached in a six-month labor dispute The strike at <LOCATION> Leonardo </LOCATION> da Vinci airport involved about 90 percent of the check-in counter personnel and baggage handlers. It was called by autonomous groups in defiance of <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>'s major labor federations. <ORGANIZATION> Alitalia </ORGANIZATION> canceled 30 flights scheduled from 1 p.m. to 8 p.m. Foreign carrier flights took off but only after delays ranging from 15 minutes to two hours. Some travelers were forced to lug baggage onto the tarmac to jet cargo holds. On Saturday, Transport Minister <PERSON> Calogero </PERSON> <PERSON> Mannino </PERSON> and federation leaders for airport ground workers announced a tentative accord in the dispute, which has been punctuated by day-long strikes a few times a month since September. The tentative accord, which would be applied retroactively from January, calls for a monthly raise of about $ 190 over three years and gradually shortening the work week from 40 -LCB- hours to 37 -LCB- hours. A baggage handler's current maximum regular salary is about $ 1,215 a month. Airport sources said the workers who struck Sunday want the salary increases granted over a shorter period. Travelers since fall have also suffered through pilot and traffic controllers' strikes as well as repeated walkouts by railway workers in still unresolved disputes. Railway workers in <LOCATION> Palermo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Sicily </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Reggio </LOCATION> di <LOCATION> Calabria </LOCATION> in southern <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, called a three hour strike for Sunday night.
