<HEAD>Hundreds Gather to Press Annexation Appeal, Condemn Soviet Press</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: DELETES redundant 9th graf</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MOS4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Hundreds of Armenians gathered Sunday at a cemetery to demand justice from the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> in a territorial dispute between <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION> and to condemn the Soviet press for being `` criminally silent.'' The fight for control of the <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION> region in <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION> has brought ethnic tensions to the surface in both southern republics. The Armenian capital of <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION> last month was the scene of a weeklong demonstration involving hundreds of thousands, and an ethnic riot in the Azerbaijani city of <LOCATION> Sumgait </LOCATION> killed at least 32. Sunday's five-hour demonstration outside a 19th century Armenian church at the <LOCATION> Vagankovskoye </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cemetery </LOCATION> swelled to as many as 1,000 participants and curious onlookers. It was the second mass gathering in less than a week by <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s Armenian community. Armenians hoisted banners declaring `` <LOCATION> Karabakh </LOCATION> was and will be Armenian'' and `` Shame to the Proponents of Genocide.'' A cluster of Armenian officials and activists, some of whom had traveled to <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> from the republic to press the annexation cause, vied for a chance to address the crowd. Armenian film director <PERSON> Boris </PERSON> <PERSON> Baratov </PERSON> told the crowd that the kind of Moslem fanaticism he believes was the catalyst for the <LOCATION> Sumgait </LOCATION> rioting can not be tolerated in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. `` If this happened to the Armenians yesterday, it can happen to any nationality tomorrow,'' he shouted. The Armenians burst into applause and shouts of approval. <PERSON> Baratov </PERSON> said he was a member of a committee of 600 Armenians from all regions and professions that has come together to keep the public informed and to press government bodies to resolve the dispute over <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION>, a mountainous region, smaller than <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION>, located within the republic of <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION>. More than three quarters of the population of the region, which was part of <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> until 1923, is Armenian. `` The silence in the press over what happened in <LOCATION> Sumgait </LOCATION> drew me into this committee,'' said <PERSON> Baratov </PERSON>, who lives in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. `` Our press has been criminally silent.'' The official <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> news agency issued a brief report on the <LOCATION> Sumgait </LOCATION> rioting which was published by the major national newspapers. But reference to the issue behind the rioting _ the annexation question _ has been made only in small-circulation newspapers in <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>. Soviet television and the government newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Izvestia </ORGANIZATION> initially branded the annexation drive an `` extremist action,'' which angered many Armenians who consider themselves moderates and loyal Soviets. Later in the rally, another member of the committee, <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> lawyer <PERSON> Garik </PERSON> <PERSON> Agabekov </PERSON>, urged the crowd to maintain order if they wanted to succeed in getting the government's support. Agabekov credited Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s reforms for allowing the long-simmering dispute over the <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION> region to be discussed and decided openly, but challenged the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> to abide by its slogans and let the region's people decide their fate. <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and government officials in <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION> voted in early February for annexation to <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>, but the party's national <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> rejected the appeal in mid-February The rejection touched off mass protests in <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION>'s central city, <LOCATION> Stepanakert </LOCATION> Unrest spread to <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION> in late February when Armenians learned that Soviet troops had moved into the disputed region to quell the protests. The <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION> demonstrations subsided after <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> appealed for calm and promised a top-level review of the annexation appeal. The ethnic rioting on Feb. 28 in <LOCATION> Sumgait </LOCATION> was reportedly sparked by Moslem extremists angered over the Armenian claims to <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION>. Most Armenians are Christian, while the <LOCATION> Azeri </LOCATION> population of <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION> is predominantly Moslem.
