<HEAD>Exploding Snail Brings Fame, Not Blame, To Restaurant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Chuck </PERSON> <PERSON> Pascale </PERSON> thought an exploding snail had blown his 5-year-old restaurant business to smithereens. Instead, it brought nationwide fame. <PERSON> Karen </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Prouty </PERSON> was celebrating her 36th birthday with a dinner at <ORGANIZATION> Pascale </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Restaurant on Feb 26. She was eating her second escargot when it blew up in her face. Garlic butter caused minor burns around her right eye and blinded her for 90 minutes. <PERSON> Prouty </PERSON> was treated at a hospital and released the same evening. The snail's internal moisture had apparently built up steam that propelled it right out of its depression in a ceramic serving dish, <PERSON> Pascale </PERSON> theorized. <PERSON> Pascale </PERSON> said he pleaded with the local newspaper not to print a story on the incident fearing it would hurt business. But he said the night the article was printed, escargot was the most popular item at the restaurant. Every snail in the building was sold, he said. `` We've won national awards for four consecutive years, and we've been nominated for a fourth star in <ORGANIZATION> Mobil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Travel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guide </ORGANIZATION>,'' said <PERSON> Pascale </PERSON>'s brother and partner, <PERSON> Neal </PERSON> <PERSON> Pascale </PERSON>. `` But this definitely added to our national reputation.'' The Pascale brothers and <PERSON> Etienne </PERSON> <PERSON> Merle </PERSON> are partners in the establishment, which specializes in French and northern Italian cuisine. Since the story was publicized nationally, the Pascales have fielded about 30 calls from radio stations and newspapers around the country. Friends and business associates have mailed them newspaper clippings about their exploding snail from <LOCATION> Lo