llect 23 while 15 will be uncommitted and six went to <PERSON> Gore </PERSON>. There are also four so-called super delegates from the state. Nationally, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s delegate total lags behind that of <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. The <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> governor has 460.5; <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> has 423.55. <PERSON> Carol </PERSON> <PERSON> Kahre </PERSON> of the state <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> said the estimated turnout of 45,000 easily surpassed the old record of about 25,000 set back in 1976. She said it could be a couple of days before all the figures from the counties are tabulated. `` The problem now becomes the county party priorities are preparing for their county conventions,'' she said, adding state officials must `` beg a lot'' to get all the numbers in. There's no official state certification of the results, she said. The credentials of each delegate will be checked at the county conventions and then again at the state convention. The record turnout for the meetings `` slowed them up and slowed up the reporting. But that's a nice kind of problem to have,'' she added. <PERSON> Earl </PERSON> <PERSON> Black </PERSON>, a political science professor at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carolina </ORGANIZATION>, said the record turnout was due to `` a flurry of final days campaign activity.'' `` I'm certain the proportion of black voters at the Democratic caucuses was higher than the overall percentage of black voters'' in the state, he said. `` With <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> being <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s home state, there was a very strong incentive in the black community. `` Some of it was due to <PERSON> Gore </PERSON>'s showing on Super Tuesday. Some Democrats felt that there was -LRB- another -RRB- candidat