<HEAD>Transition In Tactics For Bush As Grip On Nomination Tightens</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Now that <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has virtually locked up the Republican presidential nomination, he is carefully putting some distance between himself and some elements of the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration record. In a major switch in campaign strategy, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> also is trying to broaden his appeal to Democrats and independents _ a massive block of voters that <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> tapped successfully in 1980 and 1984. The vice president signaled this transition in tactics the day after his most impressive electoral performance ever _ a stunning sweep of the 16 <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> primaries on Super Tuesday. `` The message will have to be fleshed out more, and more definitive,'' he said. <PERSON> Craig </PERSON> <PERSON> Fuller </PERSON>, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s chief of staff, said `` we do n't want to get out ahead of ourselves and launch a national campaign before we get the nomination. But I think you'll see him beginning to talk more about various issues.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> later departed abruptly from his basic stump speech. He told an audience of <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> boosters in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> Thursday that if elected he would create a special White House office on ethics and devise a new ethics code. It was a concrete proposal on a general campaign theme he has pitched since last fall. `` I am tired of being embarrassed'' by news accounts of ethical misdeeds by government officials, he said. He said his call for a White House ethics office should not be taken as criticism of President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. He said he was talking about `` how I would do it.'' In another part of the speech, he offered details on how he would try to attack federal budget deficits _ going beyond a four-year, flexible spending freeze proposed earlier. He said he would take a `` hands-on'' role as a participant in negotiations with congressional leaders. The Tower commission set up to investigate the Iran-Contra affair concluded, among other things, that policy-making went awry because of <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s hands-off management style. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> had said early in his campaign that he intended eventually to talk of `` shades of difference'' in how he would approach things, as opposed to <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. And that's what happened Thursday. The <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tribune </ORGANIZATION>, endorsing Sen. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> over <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> in the next day's newspaper, said: `` Nowhere have the Republican candidates asked or answered the kind of harsh questions the Democrats surely will raise in November about the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration, whose colors Mr. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has been able to wave more furiously than anyone else.'' So, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s decision to hammer away at the theme of lifting the level of ethics in government seems to be an attempt to position the candidate to better cope with the Iran-Contra issue, the investigations of Attorney General <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> and the convictions of former <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> officials <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Deaver </PERSON> and <PERSON> Lyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Nofziger </PERSON>. Campaign manager <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Atwater </PERSON> said `` it was a big mistake'' for <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> to continue running campaign advertisements questioning <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s role in supporting the arms-to-Iran initiative. `` This has created a lot of resentment in the <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>,'' he said. But <PERSON> Atwater </PERSON> and other top <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> strategists know they have not heard the last of the issue, particularly in view of the continuing investigation of the Iran-Contra affair by special counsel <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON>. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> could find himself trying to campaign against a Democrat at a time when administration figures are being indicted and tried in connection with the scandal. The shift in <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s strategy apparently resulted from a conclusion that the vice president has sufficient strength _ with 705 of the 1,139 delegates needed to win the nomination _ to shift toward a broader-based campaign. A dual purpose would be to lessen his vulnerability to criticism by a Democratic opponent of the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration's record on ethics and to reach out to blue-collar voters, Democrats, independents and others who have supported President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> in the past. `` I do think we'll reach out to ethnic groups and various minority groups,'' <PERSON> Fuller </PERSON> said of the emerging <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> strategy. `` He has consciously reached out to the Hispanic population in the southwest and to Cubans in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>. I think he will work very hard to capture ethnic groups.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> also can be expected to touch up his campaign pitch to appeal to workers _ as he did in acknowledging that not everyone has benefited from the economic recovery. He said the face of a jobless man in <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> looks just as grim as the face of a man out of work in <LOCATION> Savannah </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ga </LOCATION>.
