<HEAD>Cold Weather Across Most Of The Nation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 The storm system that dumped heavy snow on the Plains had moved into <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> and weakened Sunday, and in its wake below-normal temperatures extended from the <ORGANIZATION> Rockies </ORGANIZATION> to the Appalachians. Afternoon temperatures were below the freezing mark across much of the northern and central Rockies, northern and central Plains and the Great Lakes region. During the night, freezing temperatures were expected to extend as far south as much of <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> and most of the lower <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>, except the Gulf Coast. Freeze warnings were posted for all of <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> except coastal sections and for the Hill Country of southern <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. Snow showers extended from the upper <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> across the Great Lakes to the upper <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>. Two to 4 inches of snow fell during the morning in snow belt areas near <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Superior </LOCATION>. A winter storm watch was posted for Monday across extreme northeastern <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> near <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Erie </LOCATION>, with as much as 8 inches possible by Monday night. Freezing rain made travel hazardous over parts of inland northern <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> during the morning, especially in some deeper valleys. Elsewhere, light snow fell over much of the <ORGANIZATION> Rockies </ORGANIZATION> during the afternoon. Up to 4 inches fell in the mountains near <LOCATION> Alamosa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colo. </LOCATION>. Showers diminished across the <LOCATION> mid-Atlantic </LOCATION> states and the <LOCATION> Carolinas </LOCATION>, but scattered thunderstorms broke out during the morning along coastal sections from <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Flor