<HEAD>Balcony Fall Victims Were Non-Students, Floridians</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Spring Break</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 One man who died after a fall from a hotel balcony and a second injured hours later at the same hotel were not part of the annual invasion by out-of-state college students, police said Sunday. With the onslaught of more than 300,000 college students on spring break, <LOCATION> Daytona </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION> authorities have been trying to crack down on such alcohol-related antics as climbing on motel balconies. In 1986, five died and seven were seriously injured in falls from high-rise motels in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>. On Saturday, <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Stricklin </PERSON>, 24, of <LOCATION> Orlando </LOCATION> leaned over the railing of a fourth-floor sundeck at the <ORGANIZATION> Seashore </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motel </ORGANIZATION> and lost his balance, police said. He was flown to <ORGANIZATION> Halifax </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, where he died of head injuries. Two hours later, <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Baldwin </PERSON>, 19, of <LOCATION> Ocala </LOCATION> fell off a second-floor roof onto the pool deck of the same hotel, and was rushed seriously injured to the same hospital. A friend told police that <PERSON> Baldwin </PERSON> had been drinking all day, said police Capt. <PERSON> Noel </PERSON> <PERSON> Ouellette </PERSON>. <PERSON> Baldwin </PERSON> was in serious condition Sunday with a concussion and facial injuries, said hospital spokeswoman <PERSON> Charlotte </PERSON> <PERSON> Hinson </PERSON>.
