<BYLINE>By BINAYA GURUACHARYA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KATMANDU, Nepal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Hundreds of Nepalese crowded hospitals Sunday and looked for relatives after a sudden hailstorm caused a stampede at a soccer stadium, killing about 90 people and injuring scores. Doctors at <LOCATION> Katmandu </LOCATION>'s main facility, the <LOCATION> Bir </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION>, said about a dozen unidentified bodies could present a health hazard because there was no place to properly store them. `` We have no room in the morgue. There is in fact no morgue to speak of in medical terms,'' said one doctor, speaking on condition of anonymity. The stampede occurred Saturday when a hailstorm struck during a soccer game at the National Stadium. Witnesses said the crowd of about 30,000 surged toward the one open exit, and many people were crushed or suffocated to death. Government television reported 73 died, and witnesses said at least 20 other bodies were taken away by relatives for cremation. More than 100 people were treated at hospitals. Three people remained in critical condition Sunday. Home Affairs Minister <PERSON> Niranjan </PERSON> <PERSON> Thapa </PERSON> said later Sunday that 70 people perished in the tragedy, including three police officers. He said 94 people had been hospitalized with injuries, and 15 remained in serious condition. <PERSON> Thapa </PERSON> denied reports that police charged crowds outside the stadium when they attacked government cars with rocks. Witnesses said police used batons to club people enraged that other gates to the stadium had not been opened. The government ordered a judicial panel to investigate the disaster and said it would pay compensation to relatives of victims and to the injured. Soccer is <LOCATION> Nepal </LOCATION>'s most popular sport, and Saturday's game was the final match in a tournament between a team from the national tobacco factory and a team from <LOCATION> Bangladesh </LOCATION>. Government-run newspapers reported that the crowd surged toward the south exit _ where most people usually enter the stadium _ but made no mention of other doors being locked. They reported that King <PERSON> Birendra </PERSON> and Queen <PERSON> Aishwarya </PERSON> visited the injured in hospitals. The official national news agency reported that the government declared a national day of mourning Sunday, a normal working day, and ordered all sports events and other entertaintment canceled. At <LOCATION> Bir </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION>, about a mile from the stadium, one patient, <PERSON> Judha </PERSON> <PERSON> Tamang </PERSON> said, `` I got blessing from our beloved king and queen.'' Hundreds of anxious people crowded around one hospital building where pictures of the unidentified dead had been posted. <PERSON> Bhayacha </PERSON> <PERSON> Kumale </PERSON>, from <LOCATION> Thimi </LOCATION>, just outside <LOCATION> Katmandu </LOCATION>, said he lost two of his sons, aged 12 and 16, in the tragedy. A third son had decided to skip Saturday's soccer game. `` I could not even give them a drop of water before they died,'' <PERSON> Kumale </PERSON> said. In <LOCATION> Nepal </LOCATION>, it is a tradition for relatives to gather at a dying person's bedside and give him water to comfort him. The stampede was <LOCATION> Nepal </LOCATION>'s worst sports-related disaster on record. It came just two days after part of a grandstand collapsed at the main soccer stadium in <LOCATION> Tripoli </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION>, reportedly killed around 20 people during a match between <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Malta </LOCATION>. Some of the 60,000 spectators at the 75,000-seat `` June 11 Stadium'' panicked when someone brandished a knife, news reports said. In the worst soccer disaster on record, rioting left nearly 300 people dead and 500 injured on May 24, 1964, in <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>, after <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> beat <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION> on a last-minute goal.
