<HEAD>World's Longest Undersea Tunnel Opens To Rail Service</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: To CORRECT that train journey is 99 miles including 33.4
miles of tunnel, subs grafs 1-3 with three grafs. Pick up 4th graf:
Excavation techniques... Deletes 15th graf bgng: Trains will be
able... which moved up.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By IRENE M. KUNII</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Passengers packed into trains and traveled under ground and sea to the island of Hokkaido on Sunday as the world's longest undersea tunnel opened to rail service Some riders had waited in line more than a week to ensure a seat on the first train that took them on the 99-mile trip from <LOCATION> Aomori </LOCATION> at the tip of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s largest island, <LOCATION> Honshu </LOCATION>, to <LOCATION> Hakodate </LOCATION> in Hokkaido, the country's northernmost main island. The Seikan Tunnel is 33.4 miles long and 14.4 miles is under water. The Aomori-Hakodate trip takes about two hours, with 30 minutes inside the tunnel. Excavation techniques developed by Japanese civil engineers for the tunnel are to be used in the construction of the planned <LOCATION> Dover </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strait </LOCATION> tunnel between <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>. Transport Minister <PERSON> Shintaro </PERSON> <PERSON> Ishihara </PERSON>, guest of honor on Sunday's first Hakodate-bound train, told Japanese reporters after crossing through the tunnel: `` It is a technological feat without parallel in the world It is a myth come true.'' Next month, with the official opening of the <LOCATION> Seto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ohashi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bridge </LOCATION>, a series of 11 spans totaling 7.6 miles linking <LOCATION> Honshu </LOCATION> with the island of <ORGANIZATION> Shikoku </ORGANIZATION>, transport officials will complete a decades-old plan of linking all four of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s main islands by rail. But the cost of the Seikan Tunnel, which took 24 years to build, has fueled debate in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> in an era of declining rail service. Overall construction and personnel outlays cost taxpayers about $ 8.5 billion at current exchange rates, well above the original forecast of $ 1.54 billion. The project also claimed the lives of 34 workers and ran 10 years behind schedule due to technical delays and four major floods. <PERSON> Yukinari </PERSON> <PERSON> Shojiguchi </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Hokkaido </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Railway </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, which will lease the tunnel from the <ORGANIZATION> Japanese </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Railway </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Construction </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, said the new undersea rail line will operate at a loss. `` But it's worth it because more people will be coming through to Hokkaido and utilizing the region, which has long been cut off from developments on the mainland,'' he said. Figures released by <ORGANIZATION> Hokkaido </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Railway </ORGANIZATION> indicate that about 2.3 million passengers and 5 million tons of cargo are likely to pass through the tunnel each year. <PERSON> Shojiguchi </PERSON> said a final estimate of operating costs still was being prepared, but did not deny reports pegging the annual level at $ 23.1 million. An 80-year-old ferry boat service between <LOCATION> Aomori </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Hakodate </LOCATION> halted operation on the eve of the tunnel's opening. Thousands of ferry fans visited the region for one last four-hour crossing over the churning <LOCATION> Tsugaru </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strait </LOCATION>, site of a ferry accident that killed more than 1,100 passengers in 1954. `` A lot of people are sorry to see the ferries go. I do n't think many will be interested in riding through a dark tunnel,'' said <PERSON> Etsuhiro </PERSON> <PERSON> Tomokane </PERSON>, a university senior from <LOCATION> Osaka </LOCATION> touring Hokkaido during a school break. But Japanese critics charge that government officials erred in approving construction of the tunnel because of the low volume of traffic across the strait, and are skeptical of claims that the tunnel will spur regional development. `` As far as the current railway service goes, it's not likely that the new tunnel will help develop the region by attracting new companies,'' said <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> Foster </PERSON>, transportation analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>. While a possible extension of the `` bullet train'' high-speed line up through the tunnel could bring a turnabout, some critics say the huge additional cost of building the line, which uses different tracks, would only increase the deficits. <PERSON> Masao </PERSON> <PERSON> Takada </PERSON>, who operates a souvenir shop in <LOCATION> Aomori </LOCATION>, says merchants on both sides of the tunnel are worried that it will hurt business. `` Surveys show that the number of customers in <LOCATION> Aomori </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Hakodate </LOCATION> will decline because train passengers on their way to <LOCATION> Sapporo </LOCATION> -LRB- in Hokkaido -RRB- from <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> are less likely to disembark and shop around,'' he said.
