<BYLINE>By BOB THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 `` The Last Emperor'' brought <PERSON> Bernardo </PERSON> <PERSON> Bertolucci </PERSON> the Directors Guild of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s feature film award, the second jewel in what may be a triple-crown season for the Italian movie director. <PERSON> Bertolucci </PERSON>, who in January won a <ORGANIZATION> Golden </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Globe </ORGANIZATION> for directing `` The Last Emperor,'' picked up the <ORGANIZATION> DGA </ORGANIZATION> award Saturday night in ceremonies held jointly at the <LOCATION> Beverly </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hilton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hotel </LOCATION> and in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> DGA </ORGANIZATION> honor boosts his odds of winning an Oscar. Only three times in the 40-year history of the award has it failed to coincide with the Academy Award direction winner. Other top <ORGANIZATION> DGA </ORGANIZATION> winners were <PERSON> Will </PERSON> <PERSON> MacKenzie </PERSON>, who received the TV comedy directing award for an episode of <ORGANIZATION> NBC-TV </ORGANIZATION>'s `` Family Ties'' called `` ` A' My Name is Alex''; and <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> <PERSON> Herskovitz </PERSON>, who won the nighttime dramatic series award for his pilot for <ORGANIZATION> ABC-TV </ORGANIZATION>'s `` thirtysomething. In all, <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> shows won three of the television direction awards, <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> won two, and <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> and PBS each won one. <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> had come in first in the number of nominations with eight. <PERSON> Bertolucci </PERSON>'s competition was <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Spielberg </PERSON> for `` Empire of the Sun,'' <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brooks </PERSON> for `` Broadcast News,'' <PERSON> Lasse </PERSON> <PERSON> Hallstrom </PERSON> for `` My Life as a Dog'' and <PERSON> Adrian </PERSON> <PERSON> Lyne </PERSON> for `` Fatal Attraction.'' In accepting his award, <PERSON> Bertolucci </PERSON> expressed his belief that `` cinema is the most international and the most classless of expressions.'' The Italian director, who won permission to film `` The Last Emperor'' in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Forbidden </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, also observed that `` cinema is living in shyness _ I might even say fear _ of television. `` Too many movies have been intimidated by television and have tried to imitate the rhythms and the language of television. Maybe I'm an idealist, but I still think of the movie theater as a cathedral where we all go together to dream the dream together.'' Other winners were: Dramatic show, daytime: <PERSON> Victoria </PERSON> <PERSON> Hochberg </PERSON>, `` Just a Regular Kid: An AIDS Story,'' <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> Afterschool Special. Musical variety: <PERSON> Dwight </PERSON> <PERSON> Hemion </PERSON>, `` <PERSON> Julie </PERSON> <PERSON> Andrews </PERSON> ... Sound of Christmas,'' an <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> special. Documentary-actuality: <PERSON> Elena </PERSON> <PERSON> Mannes </PERSON>, `` The Kingdom Divided -LRB- God and Politics -RRB-,'' on PBS. Sports: <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Fishman </PERSON>, Syracuse-Indiana <ORGANIZATION> NCAA </ORGANIZATION> basketball championship game, on <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION>. Dramatic special: <PERSON> Judd </PERSON> <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON>, `` Foxfire,'' on <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION>. Commercial directorial: <PERSON> Rick </PERSON> <PERSON> Levine </PERSON>, for three commercials: `` Trouble'' for <PERSON> Arnott </PERSON>'s Biscuits; `` <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Demby </PERSON>'' for <ORGANIZATION> DuPont </ORGANIZATION>; and `` Apt. 10-G'' for <ORGANIZATION> Pepsi </ORGANIZATION>. There also were several special achievement awards. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Wise </PERSON>, director of `` The Sound of Music'' and `` West Side Story,'' received the <PERSON> D.W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Griffith </PERSON> Award, the guild's highest honor. <PERSON> Sheldon </PERSON> <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON>, longtime <ORGANIZATION> DGA </ORGANIZATION> treasurer, was named recipient of the <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Aldrich </PERSON> Award for service to the guild. Former guild national executive director <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON>, who guided the organization through several important labor negotiations with producers, received an honorary life membership. The 8,500-member <ORGANIZATION> DGA </ORGANIZATION> represents film and television directors as well as assistant directors and production managers in movies and associate directors and stage managers in television.
