<HEAD>Soviet Officials Inspect NATO Exercise in Norway</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TROMSOE, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Four Soviet army officers flew here from <LOCATION> Leningrad </LOCATION> Sunday to observe winter maneuvers by <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treaty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> forces, the allied press information center reported. It said the Soviets would observe the military exercises for a 48-hour period. The month-long maneuvers in northern <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION> involve 14,000 military personnel from eight nations. Under a 1986 <LOCATION> Stockholm </LOCATION> agreement, any country that signed the pact has the right to inspect large-scale military exercises in other countries to ensure that aggressive actions are not being prepared. The agreement also requires member states to notify the others of such maneuvers. The agreement was ratified by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> and all European countries except <LOCATION> Albania </LOCATION>. The press center said there have been five similar observation missions. The Soviets sent observers to two <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> maneuvers in <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> sent a team to <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> had observers at one exercise in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> one in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>.
