<HEAD>Israel Chokes Off Gasoline, Death Toll Rises</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with one graf to UPDATE with Shamir leaving early
Monday. SUBS seven grafs for grafs 5-10 pvs: `Before this ...' to
UPDATE with casualty count at 91, details of Shamir airport
conference, confirmation of Mitzna order. Pickup 11th pvs: We will
... EDITS thruout to trim</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By NICOLAS B. TATRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> choked off gasoline supplies to the occupied <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> on Sunday after Palestinian protesters set fire to two fuel trucks and pelted others with stones. Prime Minister <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> flew to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> Monday to meet with <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials. The army confirmed an <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> died after being shot in the eye in a clash last week but denied reports that a 5-year-old boy perished from burns caused by a tear gas grenade. The army said the boy had been playing with a kerosene stove when he was fatally burned. A spokesman said the parents initially blamed soldiers but later retracted the allegation. A police spokesman said more than half of the 850 Arab policemen in the occupied <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> the </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION> had resigned in response to a campaign led by the <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> said at least 91 Palestinians have been killed since anti-Israeli rioting began Dec. 8 in the occupied territories. Sunday night, police and organizers estimated from 200,000 to 250,000 Israelis gathered in <LOCATION> Tel </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aviv </LOCATION> to back <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON>'s refusal to accept <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> peace proposals. At the protest, demonstrators held signs that read, `` Peace now, pay later,'' `` Yes to peace, no to withdrawal,'' and `` <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> to the Indians.'' The rally came one day after Peace Now demonstrators _ estimated by <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> newspapers at 40,000 _ protested in <LOCATION> Tel </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aviv </LOCATION>, urging <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> to accept the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> peace plan. <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON>, at an airport news conference early Monday before leaving for <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, said he felt `` at peace with himself'' in his decision to reject the plan. He added he hoped his talks with President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> would advance the peace process. After two fuel trucks were set ablaze in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and others stoned, Maj. Gen. <PERSON> Amram </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitzna </PERSON> banned fuel trucks from entering the occupied <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION>, the army reported. A senior official in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> military government said fuel would be delivered to stations that serviced hospital ambulances and certain other vehicles. `` We will arrange for fuel deliveries only to places where it is vital for public services,'' said the official, who spoke on condition of anonymity. The army confirmed economic restrictions had been imposed on the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> town of <LOCATION> Qabatiyeh </LOCATION>, where an alleged pro-Israeli collaborator was hung from an electrical pole last month after shooting a child to death. The village will be barred from exports to <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> and will be unable to receive visitors from abroad, an army official said. <LOCATION> Qabatiyeh </LOCATION> is also without electricity, he said. Defense Minister <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Rabin </PERSON> last month said <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> might have to resort to economic restrictions against the 1.5 million Arabs in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION> if strikes and violence persisted. Police ministry spokesman <PERSON> Nahum </PERSON> <PERSON> Mendel </PERSON> said 450 of 850 Arab police officers in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> had handed in their papers after underground leaflets called for their resignations. He said Israeli police might be called to help. Former police officers wearing civilian clothes could be seen leaving a district headquarters building in <LOCATION> Bethlehem </LOCATION> after making their resignations official. One of them, <PERSON> Rames </PERSON>, 33, who declined to give his last name, said he was influenced by last week's brutal slaying in <LOCATION> Jericho </LOCATION> of a police officer who was accused of being a collaborator. `` The killing made me decide very quickly,'' he said. Dozens of <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> tax collectors also have resigned, and Palestinians have been called on to stop paying taxes. But a senior Israeli official said tax receipts were down only about 10 percent for January and February. A military court, meanwhile, indicted a soldier from the elite <ORGANIZATION> Givati </ORGANIZATION> brigade for manslaughter. An army spokesman said the soldier was en route to an army base when his car was surrounded by stone-throwers. The soldier drew his weapon and shot a Palestinian who cursed him, the spokesman said. <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> cleared the way for the deportation of three more Palestinians after rejecting an appeal and lifting a temporary restraining order that had barred their expulsion. The three were detained before the current unrest. Nine other Palestinians were handed deportation orders Jan. 3, and four were flown to southern <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> on Jan 12. The move drew strong international protests as a violation of Geneva Conventions on the treatment of civilians in occupied zones. The divided Cabinet debated the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> peace proposals, and <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> said the 24-member body would vote on the plan after he returns from his eight-day <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> visit. <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> has rejected several key elements of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> plan, especially its call for an international conference. But he apparently held out hope of getting <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> agreement for changes. The plan also calls for Palestinian self-rule in the occupied lands. <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> Israel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> radio </ORGANIZATION> that he would propose revisions to the plan.
