<HEAD>Celebrators Conga Their Way To Apparent World Record</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES MARTINEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Forming the world's longest conga line with almost 120,000 dancers was no problem Sunday for members of the crowd that filled the streets of <LOCATION> Little </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Havana </LOCATION> for the Calle Ocho festival. `` It's very easy: Just face toward downtown, grab the shoulders of the person in front of you _ and dance,'' <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Sanchez </PERSON>, organizer of the event. <PERSON> Anna </PERSON> <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON>, a representative of the <ORGANIZATION> Guinness </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Book </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Records </ORGANIZATION>, confirmed a record had been set at 119,986 dancers, shattering the old mark of a 10,442-person chain formed last August in <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>. `` There's no way it could fail. As soon as the music plays, we just grab on to somebody and hang on,'' said <PERSON> Nuvia </PERSON> <PERSON> Valdez </PERSON>, one of about 1.5 million who turned out for the food and fun of what is billed as the nation's largest Hispanic festival. The river of people along 23 blocks of Eighth Street _ <LOCATION> Calle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ocho </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Spanish </LOCATION> _ began to move when <PERSON> Gloria </PERSON> <PERSON> Estefan </PERSON> and the <ORGANIZATION> Miami </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sound </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Machine </ORGANIZATION> blared their hit `` Conga'' from loudspeakers. On the street, 96 volunteers with bullhorns attempted to direct the traffic of dancing feet, while Ms. <PERSON> Estefan </PERSON> shouted to the crowd: `` Is everybody ready? Let's conga!'' A special computer program helped count the dancers, and 30 observation posts were set up. Since the street was clogged, forming a single line was difficult, and untold thousands of people formed in a bevy of smaller lines in addition to the mega-line that made the Guinness tally. `` I've never seen this many people in one place in my life,'' said <PERSON> Jean-Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> Levasseur </PERSON>, who was vacationing from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Brunswick </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>. `` There's more people on this one street than in all of the Maritime Provinces.''
