<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>'s political turmoil has been a wrenching experience for three Panamanian diplomats who are defying the sentiments of most of their <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> colleagues by remaining loyal to embattled strongman <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>. Two are described by acquaintances as showing signs of emotional stress as a result of <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>'s ordeal while a third has remained holed up in the country's consular affairs office since the crisis began more than two weeks ago. Most Panamanians attached to diplomatic offices in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> closed ranks around Ambassador <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sosa </PERSON>, who refused to recognize the February 26 change in government in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> and continues to support ousted President <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> Arturo </PERSON> <PERSON> Delvalle </PERSON>. With <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> backing, <PERSON> Sosa </PERSON> has declined to relinquish control over the embassy despite efforts by the Noriega-controlled government to replace him. A number of Panamanian diplomats elsewhere have broken with <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> as well. The latest known case involves the consul general in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Jaime </PERSON> <PERSON> Trujillo </PERSON>, who notified <PERSON> Sosa </PERSON> on Thursday that to continue supporting the present leadership `` would contribute to the disintegration of the Panamanian family.'' The three Panamanians in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> who have stuck with <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> have close personal ties to the defense chief or his inner circle, according to friends and colleagues, all of whom insisted on anonymity. <PERSON> Roberto </PERSON> <PERSON> Leyton </PERSON>, who has known <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> for years, is <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>'s ambassad