But a Panamanian diplomat who has been in contact with <PERSON> Motta </PERSON> said the captain has been under a doctor's care recently for high blood pressure, a condition which worsened after the crisis erupted. His appearances at the embassy have been more infrequent lately, and he often stays only for a few minutes before departing. The relationship between <PERSON> Motta </PERSON> and others at the embassy is said to have become strained. <PERSON> Sosa </PERSON> has told <PERSON> Motta </PERSON> that he wants to keep lines of communication open in the event that <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> wishes to send messages to the ambassador through <PERSON> Motta </PERSON>. Thus far, no communications have been sent. A senior <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> official said <PERSON> Motta </PERSON> has been in contact with defense officials in an attempt to learn what the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government is doing in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>. `` He's trying to figure out what's going on ... so he can report back to his boss,'' the official said. `` But he's not in any position of trying to broker a deal. And he's not contacting us nearly as much as before.''
