<HEAD>Sandinista Party Calls On Opposition to Renew National Dialogue</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RODOLFO GARCIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The ruling <ORGANIZATION> Sandinista </ORGANIZATION> party invited opposition parties and groups Sunday to renew stalled talks with the government on national reconciliation. President <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON>, reading a statement from top party officials, called for a resumption of talks that would, `` in a serene manner, discuss all the political points that could preoccupy'' the civic opposition. The Sandinista statement also said the government would redouble its efforts `` to reach an effective cease-fire'' during talks with leaders of the U.S.-supported Contra rebels scheduled for March 21-23 in the southern border town of <LOCATION> Sapoa </LOCATION>. Talks between the leftist government and its internal opposition are called for in a Central American peace plan signed by five presidents in the region last Aug. 7. The directorate and assembly urged opposition parties, labor unions, trade guilds and media `` not to continue provoking situations that explode the public wrath.'' Government talks began Oct. 5 with 15 opposition parties, but stalled Dec. 15 when the government refused to discuss 17 opposition proposals to modify a new national political Constitution, which went into effect in January. <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> accused opposition party leaders at the time of allowing themselves to be used as instruments by the <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> in its efforts to launch an invasion of <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>. The Sandinistas maintained that any modifications to the Constitution would have to be addressed by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION>. Sandinista delegates comprise a majority in the Assembly. <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Bonilla </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> party </ORGANIZATION> told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZAT