<HEAD>Nuclear Plant Shuts Down Two Days After It Finally Opens</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OSWEGO, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Nine Mile 2 nuclear power plant, which began providing power on a permanent basis Friday for the first time in its troubled existence, automatically shut down Sunday night when a water pump malfunctioned, a plant official said. The $ 6.3 billion facility, described as the most expensive nuclear plant ever built in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, underwent what officials term an `` unusual event'' at 5:45 p.m. Sunday. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Burtch </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Niagara </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mohawk </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, said the problem occurred when the plant lost its main feed water pump, which provides water pressure to the reactor. `` The plant was operating at 99 percent power,'' <PERSON> Burtch </PERSON> said. `` But when that -LRB- the water pump -RRB- tripped, the water level in the reactor dropped and caused the plant to automatically shut down.'' <PERSON> Burtch </PERSON> said the actual problem was corrected within 15 minutes and the water in the plant was quickly replenished. `` But any time there's an automatic activation of an emergency cooling system,'' he added, `` we have to activate the emergency plan.'' The `` unusual event'' is the lowest emergency classification that exists for nuclear plants. Officials declined to speculate when the plant might return to full power. `` We're looking right now to determine the cause, but obviously we're not going to start back up until we know what went wrong,'' <PERSON> Burtch </PERSON> said Sunday night. `` We'll know more tomorrow.'' The 1,080-megawatt plant, which was supposed to have been completed in 1977 at a cost of $ 423 million, began providing power on a permanent basis when plant operators declared it `` on-line'' around 3 p.m. Friday.
