<HEAD>Amnesty International accuses Burma of human rights violations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> claims that <LOCATION> Burmese </LOCATION> government forces have arbitrarily arrested, tortured and executed hundreds of unarmed civilians since fighting against rebels intensified in 1984. The London-based organization said that its interviews with more than 70 refugees and statements from independent investigators have produced the names of more than 200 victims, most of whom belonged to minority ethnic tribes including the <LOCATION> Karens </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kachins </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mons </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Kayahs </PERSON> and Shans. In its February newsletter, the human rights organization said the victims were attacked `` apparently because of their non-violent political opinions or activities, their ethnic origins or language.'' The newsletter was available Monday in <LOCATION> Bangkok </LOCATION>. It said the <LOCATION> Burmese </LOCATION> government has not responded to several letters in which <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> expressed its concern. A dozen ethnic groups have been fighting the <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION> government for decades, saying it has denied them the autonomy they were entitled to under the terms in which <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> granted independence to <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION> in 1948. The newsletter said most of the people it blamed for human rights violations were army troops engaged in counter-insurgency operations in zones suspected of being under rebel influence. Members of the <ORGANIZATION> Military </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intelligence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, the Special Branch and the <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> also were implicated, it said. `` Eyewitnesses describe numerous insta