<HEAD>Japanese Government Delays Taking Stand On Panama</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELAINE KURTENBACH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Recent political developments in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> have put <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> in the awkward position of having to choose between pleasing <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> or maintaining good relations with its top Latin American trading partner. Foreign Ministry officials have withheld an official position on the government installed by military strongman Gen. <PERSON> Manual </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> as <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> apparently plays for time, hoping to avoid aggravating the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, which regards ousted President <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> Arturo </PERSON> <PERSON> Delvalle </PERSON> as <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>'s legitimate ruler. But <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s considerable commercial interests in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> give <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> strong incentive to maintain good relations with <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>'s government <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> is not only a major consumer of Japanese goods, it also controls the <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canal </LOCATION>, a vital link for Japanese cars headed for the eastern <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and agricultural products returning to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. On Feb. 25, <PERSON> Delvalle </PERSON> ordered the resignation of <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>, who is under indictment in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> on drug trafficking charges. The next day, however, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION>, controlled by <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>, dismissed <PERSON> Delvalle </PERSON> and appointed <PERSON> Solis </PERSON> <PERSON> Palma </PERSON> as president. Last week, the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> asked Japanese Counselor for Political Affairs <PERSON> Ryozo </PERSON> <PERSON> Kato </PERSON> to explain <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>'s position on <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>'s government. Assistant Secretary of State <PERSON> Elliott </PERSON> <PERSON> Abrams </PERSON> in turn explained <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s opposition to <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>. Foreign Ministry officials in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> say <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> simply has not decided whether to recognize <PERSON> Palma </PERSON>'s government. They refused to give any indication of when such a decision will be made. Rumors that <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> had in effect recognized the new government by sending its ambassador to <PERSON> Palma </PERSON>'s inauguration were untrue, said one ministry official. `` The presense of our counselor, instead of the ambassador to <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>, at <LOCATION> Palma </LOCATION>'s inaugural ceremony is a sign of uncertainty,'' said the official, speaking on condition of anonymity. `` We have not yet decided.'' <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> may find it difficult to distance itself from <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>, who has visited <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> several times in recent years in his capacity as head of <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>'s armed forces. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> has a $ 3.2 billion trade surplus with <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>, and is <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>'s second-largest trading partner after the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. In turn, <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> is <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s largest export market in <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, as well as the top recipient of Japanese direct investment in the region. <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> absorbed $ 2.4 billion, or 51 percent, of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s private direct investment in <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> in 1986 _ one-tenth of all direct investment by Japanese companies. It received 41 percent of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s $ 15.6 billion accumulative direct investment in the region from 1951 to 1985, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>. Japanese companies have financed economic development projects, medical and educational facilities in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>. A <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said that aside from a halt to all banking activities, which has prevented business among Japanese banks operating in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>, recent political unrest has had little effect on Japanese commercial activities in the nation. `` So far there is no cause to expect any major problems,'' she said. Since banks can no longer issue letters of credit, `` In <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>, everyday is Sunday,'' said <PERSON> Masaya </PERSON> <PERSON> Hasebe </PERSON> of the <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> External Trade Organization -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> JETRO </ORGANIZATION> -RRB-. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> lawmakers including Sen. <PERSON> Alfonse </PERSON> <PERSON> D'Amato </PERSON>, who favors a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade embargo against <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>, have expressed concern that <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> might follow its economic interests in recognizing <PERSON> Palma </PERSON>'s government <PERSON> D'Amato </PERSON> said a number of legislators hoped to see `` that the Japanese do not become involved in helping to finance and prop up this dictator for their own private economic gain.'' <ORGANIZATION> JETRO </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Hasebe </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> probably would `` have to cooperate'' with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and reject <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>'s government _ a move that could have some economic costs. `` There are many banks and manufacturers with businesses in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>, but no factories,'' <PERSON> Hasebe </PERSON> said. He said some of the Japanese firms are paper companies set up as tax havens. While <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> has given no official indication that it would recognize the government put in place by <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> has a clear interest in ensuring its access to the <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canal </LOCATION>. Japanese ships accounted for 13.1 percent of the 64.5 million tons of cargo shipped through the canal from the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> to the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> in the 1985 fiscal year ending in September 1986, including many of its cars destined for markets in the eastern <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. In the same period, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> accounted for 26.1 million tons, or 35.2 percent of the total 74.2 million tons shipped from <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> ships petroleum from <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION>, grain from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and iron ore from <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> through the canal. <PERSON> Hasebe </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> JETRO </ORGANIZATION> said there was little concern that the canal, which is jointly operated by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>, would be closed to traffic. `` All the government can do right now is wait and see, looking at the future of <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>,'' he said.
