<HEAD>Three Missing Zeroes Could Cost Prudential Millions Of Dollars</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Prudential </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> may be about to lose an ally in the case of the missing zeroes, a clerical error on a financial document that could cost the company tens of millions of dollars. In a case that is the talk of the town among bankruptcy lawyers, <ORGANIZATION> Prudential </ORGANIZATION> is trying to establish in court that a mortgage lien it holds is for $ 92,885,000. The problem is that someone mistakenly left three zeroes off a form and recorded the lien's value as only $ 92,885 _ one-tenth of 1 percent as much. The lien is on eight huge container ships that belonged to <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lines </LOCATION>, a giant shipping company whose assets are being sold off to satisfy creditors in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Bankruptcy Court in <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lines </LOCATION> agreed in principle in January not to contest <ORGANIZATION> Prudential </ORGANIZATION>'s claims about the value of its lien in return for payments from <ORGANIZATION> Prudential </ORGANIZATION> totaling up to $ 5.45 million. But with a hearing to wrap up that agreement scheduled for this Wednesday before Judge <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Buschman </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lines </LOCATION> seems to be on the verge of demanding a larger payment from <ORGANIZATION> Prudential </ORGANIZATION> _ and possibly challenging the lien's validity if <ORGANIZATION> Prudential </ORGANIZATION> does n't go along. Because <ORGANIZATION> Prudential </ORGANIZATION> holds a first preferred ship mortgage stemming from a $ 160 milion loan to <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lines </LOCATION> made in 1978, it can collect all the money raised from the sale of the eight ships, up to the amount of its lien. A lawyer for <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lines </LOCATION> last week refused to say whether the company planned to oppose <ORGANIZATION> Prudential </ORGANIZATION> over the missing zeroes, but made it clear he feels the shipping company has leverage over the insurer. `` We believe we're on sound ground that the mortgage can be avoided for the benefit of all <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Line </ORGANIZATION>'s creditors,'' said <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Kornberg </PERSON>, a lawyer for <ORGANIZATION> Milbank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tweed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hadley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> McCloy </PERSON>. The sale of the first five of the Lancer-class ships earlier this month brought in $ 44.1 million, nearly triple what was expected, and other creditors are clamoring that <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> States </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lines </ORGANIZATION> deserves a payment from <ORGANIZATION> Prudential </ORGANIZATION> of more than $ 5.45 million. <PERSON> Judy </PERSON> <PERSON> Liu </PERSON>, an attorney for <ORGANIZATION> Prudential </ORGANIZATION>'s law firm, <ORGANIZATION> Weil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gotshal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manges </ORGANIZATION>, declined to comment. Lawyers in the case clearly have little sympathy for <ORGANIZATION> Prudential </ORGANIZATION>'s argument that the dropped zeroes amount to nothing more than a harmless mistake. `` The Federal Ship Mortgage Act is a notice statute that has very strict reporting requirements,'' said <PERSON> Sandy </PERSON> <PERSON> Mayerson </PERSON>, a lawyer at <ORGANIZATION> Kelley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drye </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Warren </PERSON> representing <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Capital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, which shares a second mortgage on the ships. `` My client actually lent $ 57 million to the debtor, so anything it does to try to obtain the repayment of that is certainly to be expected,'' she said. <ORGANIZATION> Prudential </ORGANIZATION> says the lien was improperly recorded by someone at the law firm of <LOCATION> Haight </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Gardner </PERSON>, Poor and Havens. It says if its lien is not upheld it may file malpractice suits against <PERSON> Haight </PERSON>, <PERSON> Gardner </PERSON> and its overall outside counsel on the transaction, <LOCATION> Dewey </LOCATION>, Ballantine, <PERSON> Bushby </PERSON>, <PERSON> Palmer </PERSON> and <PERSON> Wood </PERSON>. Attorneys for those firms have declined comment on the malpractice matter.
