<HEAD>Japanese Chip Shortage Hits U.S. Computer Industry</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A shortage of Japanese computer chips is rattling the domestic computer industry, with prices of some important memory chips doubling in the past year, according to a published report. The <ORGANIZATION> San </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Francisco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Examiner </ORGANIZATION> reported in its Sunday editions that chips selling under contract for $ 2.15 a year ago now are in short supply, and their prices have shot up to the $ 5 range. Some companies are buying chips on the spot market at even higher prices to get extra supplies. `` The price of chips is out of hand,'' said <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Cavuto </PERSON>, editor of an industry newsletter, Micro Publishing Report. `` Chips are the fuel of the computer industry. It keeps us running and there should be an unlimited supply.'' Some industry observers trace the problem to a 1986 semiconductor trade agreement between the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. The accord set up fair market value prices for semiconductors, such as essential memory chips used in computers. It banned third-country dumping and the Japanese agreed to open up their economy more to American products. But at the time, most <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> companies had dropped out of the memory chip business completely. Only two companies, <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Instruments </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>, and <ORGANIZATION> Micron </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technology </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boise </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>, still make dynamic random access memory chips, or D-RAMs, an essential memory chip for semiconductors. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> has 90 percent of the D-RAM market, according to the <ORGANIZATION> San </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jose </ORGANIZATION> market research company, <ORGANIZATION> Dataquest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> `` We send our procurement people to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> all the time and use every bit of leverage we can bring to bear to make sure we're getting our share,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Young </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Hewlett-Packard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. Semiconductor makers in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> deny they deliberately are short-changing <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> They say the time-consuming conversion of factories to develop D-RAMs instead of 256 kilobit chips and increased demand have caused the chip shortage. `` They -LRB- Japanese suppliers -RRB- have to wait and see to avoid oversupply and charges of dumping,'' said <PERSON> Michihiro </PERSON> <PERSON> Inoue </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Matsushita </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electrical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Osaka </LOCATION>. `` It takes time to put a new production system into orbit.'' <PERSON> Inoue </PERSON> predicted Japanese companies would catch up with chip demand later this year.
