er </PERSON> dipped 25 cents to $ 17.37 -LCB-. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> McGrath </PERSON>, a spokesman for <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION>, said an offer of more than $ 75 a share would top <ORGANIZATION> Black </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Decker </PERSON>'s current offer and would relegates <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION>'s own defensive recapitalization plan _ which would pay shareholders a package of cash and securities valued at about $ 71 a share _ to a back burner. <PERSON> McGrath </PERSON> declined to give other information about third-party offers or to disclose how many bidders were involved in discussions with <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION>, a plumbing and air conditioning manufacturing company. `` This -LRB- $ 75 bid -RRB- emerged from the discussions,'' he said. While noting there was no assurance the $ 75 bid would be accepted, <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> cited the new developments in saying it would drop its poison pill, which makes a takeover prohibitively expensive by requiring the surviving company to buy back shareholders' stock at half of market value. `` Noboby could have done it with the poison pill,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Lucas </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> has fought <ORGANIZATION> Black </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Decker </PERSON>'s bid for months, rejecting its overtures, developing the recapitalization plan to thwart the takeover and winning a court battle validating its poison pill. Black & amp; <PERSON> Decker </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> Towson </LOCATION>, Md.-based tool and appliance maker, initially offered a buyout at $ 65 a share, later sweeteni